<1ST_LINE>s a BC-Atlanta'sProWoes Adv17-18   12-14 1151</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Atlanta's Pro Woes, Adv17-18,1181</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Dec. 17-18</NOTE>
<HEAD>Braves and Falcons Look to Move to the Suburbs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on sports wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When it opened, it was a blue and white miracle in
concrete and steel, built in a civic frenzy to bring major league
sports to the South.
   Twenty-three years later, Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium finds
itself a pariah among ballparks, a place that both its tenants _
baseball's Braves and football's Falcons _ are desperately trying to
flee even before the mortgage is paid off.
   Grumbling about the stadium has gone on for years.
   The round configuration isn't perfect for baseball, and for
football, everyone agrees, it's worse _ when the rectangular field
is fitted in beneath the circular stands, the usually desirable
50-yard-line seats are farthest away from the action.
   Dirty concourses and disgusting restrooms led some in recent
years to dub it ``Atlanta-Filthy County Stadium.'' The quality of
the playing field has drawn complaints from Atlanta players and
opposing teams alike. Narrow concourses leave little room for modern
concession areas.
   Still, the downtown stadium is structurally sound, repainted and
looking pretty good, although the restrooms can still get unpleasant.
   But 1988 may be remembered as the beginning of the end for
Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium.
   Both the Falcons and the Braves insist they will not sign up for
another hitch after their leases run out in 1990. It is now possible
that within the next decade, the city of Atlanta, once home to five
major-league sports franchises, will be down to one, its once proud
stadium bulldozed and the land sold to pay off the debts.
   ``I don't enjoy hearing things like that,'' said Ivan Allen Jr.,
the dynamic mayor of Atlanta from 1961-69 who still boasts of how he
and his city built a major league ballpark ``on ground we didn't
own, with money we didn't have, for a team we hadn't signed.''
   ``I walked around the stadium (at the Dec. 4 Falcons game) and it
was in excellent condition,'' Allen said recently. ``It could be
used, and be in good shape, for a long time.''
   But it appears it won't be.
   In 1986, a civic panel recommended two new stadiums: a domed
football arena adjoining the Georgia World Congress Center
convention facility downtown by 1990, and a new baseball park at the
present stadium site by '95.
   In 1987, Falcons owner Rankin M. Smith Sr., long fed up with a
lease that benefits the Braves, with a lack of luxury boxes and with
the stadium itself, said he would not renew it.
   Since then Smith has, at various times, discussed playing in the
proposed ``Georgia Dome,'' building an open-air stadium near the
team's suburban Gwinnett County training complex, 30 miles from
downtown Atlanta, and even moving the franchise to football-hungry
Jacksonville, Fla., and its 80,000-seat Gator Bowl.
   The Falcons are gone, concedes Reggie Williams, the stadium
authority's executive director since April 1987.
   ``I'd say so. ... I can understand that the football people here
need to leave to get into an environment where they can share in
other ... revenues.''
   Then, earlier this month, Atlanta Braves President Stan Kasten
dropped a bombshell: The Braves aren't staying either.
   The Braves, he said, are holding ``very serious discussions''
about moving to a proposed state-of-the-art baseball stadium in
Gwinnett County.
   Kasten, in a recent interview, said detailing the problems with
the stadium would take ``a laundry list.'' He mentioned specifically
the lack of modern amenities and the round configuration.
   ``Can you play baseball there? Sure you can,'' Kasten said. ``Can
you play football there? Sure you can.
   ``We just want a better place _ a place that is competitive with
the modern-day stadiums, built only for baseball. ... I'm not saying
it's unplayable. But we can do better, and if the Braves can, we
certainly should pursue that.''
   Kasten says the Braves would consider other metro Atlanta
locations, and would probably agree to stay in the current facility
until that new downtown baseball stadium _ ``which we were promised,
really'' in the 1986 plans _ can be built in the mid-90s.
   But the proposed $159 million football dome remains tangled in
financial and political haggling, and the subsequent $60 million
baseball stadium is not even under serious consideration yet.
   ``We're interested in getting a new facility,'' Kasten said.
``They (the city and Fulton County) don't want to talk about that.
So there's not much for us to discuss right now.''
   That leaves the Braves, in Kasten's words, ``very close to
getting into substantive, detail-type conversations'' with Gwinnett
officials. ``I've been very impressed with the enthusiasm and the
spirit I see among the people in Gwinnett,'' he said.
   The idea of the Braves and Falcons leaving Atlanta has yet to
spawn a great public outcry. The two teams have made the playoffs in
only five out of their 46 combined seasons in Atlanta, and cynics
suggest the city wouldn't miss them.
   And while most Atlanta officials are backing the dome plan for
the Falcons, they haven't exactly scurried to keep the Braves in the
city limits. Atlanta City Council President Marvin Arrington, while
accusing the Braves of racism in wanting to move to the white
suburbs, said the city would ``welcome other municipalities within
our community to shoulder more of the costs'' of pro sports.
   Both teams could be gone from the stadium by 1991 _ despite the
fact that the debts won't be paid off until 2000. The city, Williams
said, might wind up selling the land just to pay off the stadium
debts: ``The question becomes whether the value of the property is
equal to the amount of money owed.''
   All of this is a far cry from 1964, when sports in Atlanta meant
Georgia Tech or minor league baseball's Atlanta Crackers. It was
then that ground was broken for the stadium that would propel the
city _ literally and figuratively _ into the big leagues.
   Atlanta Stadium, with Ivan Allen at the whip, was built in just
51 weeks, with $14 million borrowed from booster-minded bankers. The
Braves moved from Milwaukee in 1966; the Falcons came that fall.
Within six years came basketball's Atlanta Hawks, who play in The
Omni downtown, and hockey's Flames and soccer's Chiefs, both since
departed.
   ``Twenty-five years after that stadium was built ... it's paid
for itself handsomely, with what it's done for Atlanta since then,''
Allen said. ``I certainly would have hoped it would have gone on for
a much longer time.''
   Sports in the suburbs, he said, ``would be better than not having
anything.'' But Allen thinks losing either team to the suburbs would
be a blow to the city.
   ``I think its preferable that they stay in the city of Atlanta,''
he said. ``That's the core of everything.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for weekened editionsd, Dec. 17-18</NOTE>
