<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 18, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Analyst Says Grain Imports Put Financial Burden on Soviet Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The higher cash costs of importing U.S. grain
and soybeans have caused grumbling among the Soviet Union's
financial planners and are contributing to Moscow's huge economic
problems, says an Agriculture Department economist.
   For example, in the first nine months of 1988, about $1.2 billion
worth of U.S. grain was shipped to the Soviet Union. In addition,
about $362 million worth of soybeans and soybean meal was shipped.
   In all, counting sales by other countries, the Soviets may spend
around $16.5 billion on imports of agricultural products this
calendar year, up about $1 billion from 1987, says Kathryn Zeimetz
of the department's Economic Research Service.
   ``The bill for grain, the primary farm import for which the
Soviets pay hard currency, will increase over $1 billion from 1987's
$2.6 billion, mostly because import prices are up 35 percent,'' she
said.
   It is this drain that disturbs Moscow's planners most. The main
source of hard currency for the Soviet Union is from petroleum
sales, but oil prices are down and grain prices are up.
   ``Energy sales to the West usually account for 60 percent of
Soviet hard currency receipts,'' Zeimetz said in a recent report.
``Soviet oil export prices in the first nine months of 1988 averaged
below 1986. The 15 percent to 20 percent price increase in 1987 was
more than lost in 1988.''
   Zeimetz said Soviet agricultural import volume in 1989 may be
about at the same total level, except that grain imports may be
greater.
   Overall, the cost of imports next year could rise substantially,
with grain prices rising by as much as 20 percent, she said.
   ``The cost of increased agricultural imports _ coupled with
relatively low petroleum prices, deteriorating terms of trade, and
continued need for non-agricuturl imports _ could make Soviet
traders even more exacting in 1989,'' Zeimetz said.
   Much of the Soviet Union's economic problems stem from a lack of
quality food and other consumer goods, massive consumer subsidies
for food, and higher wages. As a result, she said, there has been an
excess of consumer demand and excess savings, despite both open and
hidden inflation.
   ``The Soviets have maintained the basic prices on most
state-distributed foodstuffs at 1962 levels,'' Zeimetz said. ``These
have resulted in massive consumer subsidies as production,
processing and marketing costs have risen.''
   In 1987, the subsidies cost about 60 billion rubles, or $94
billion, she said. And they continue to rise.
   ``Although small cooperatives and individual enterprises are now
encouraged, their output of goods and services is not yet
significant,'' she said.
   Meanwhile, the average Soviet's income during the first nine
months of 1988 was reported up 9 percent from a year earlier, when
the corresponding increase was less than half as much. Deposits in
the state savings bank rose 5 percent during the period.
   Zeimetz said the Soviets ``have built modestly on the 1986
breakthrough in agricultural production, when output increased 7
percent after years of stagnation or decline. Still, per capita
production has only regained its 1976-78 average.''
   Currently, she said, the Kremlin's focus is on improving farming
practices and management, increasing competition, and raising worker
incentives by decentralizing management and financial control.
   ``Decentralization's newest aim is to establish lease
collectives, predominantly on state and collective farms, but also
on land outside the socialized farm system,'' Zeimetz said. ``Small
groups can lease land from a farm, a government agency or an
industrial firm that controls it.''
   Although leasing has produced ``phenomenal increases'' in
production, efficiency and cost savings, Zeimetz said the results
may partly reflect the attention being given the few lease units in
operation.
   Zeimetz said the potential for big gains from leasing is limited
by a number of factors:
   _Administrator and farm manager resistance to giving up control.
   _Farm worker reluctance to take risks.
   _Inadequacies of Soviet farm supplies and infrastructure.
   _Doubts about the permanence of the lease program.
   _Lack of prices determined by market demands.
   _State reluctance to allow large income disparities.
   ``A recent poll showed that only about 15 percent of the adult
population favored cooperative and individual labor activities, to
which leasing is cl she said. ``Negative attitutes
about income disparities have led to vandalism,osely related,'' and are
limiting
success not only for improved agricultural production but also for
food processing and trade, and other consumer goods and services.''
   On another front, Zeimetz said the Kremlin has tried to improve
the storage, processing and distribution of farm commodities in
order to improve the quality of food and reduce losses after
harvest, which Soviet officials estimate may exceed 25 percent of
the harvest.
   ``Recently, 70 meat processing enterprises had no refrigerators,
and of the 850 refrigerators at other enterprises, 42 percent had
been in operation for 20 to 50 years,'' she said. ``Less than 20
percent of Soviet processing machinery was up to world standards,
and 60 percent was virtually worn New York the
instant she crosses the Hudson River, returned to L.A. to do another
sitcom.
   A few weeks before CBS decided to take her show off the air,
Moore was interviewed in her trailer parked outside Stage 3 at the
MTM Studios, the same trailer she used for ``The Mary Tyler Moore
Show'' and was also once used by Judy Garland. She's on a couch,
wearing a red warm-up suit. Her light brown hair is cut stylishly
short. Up close, despite her diabetic condition and too many years
spent exposing her skin to the California sun, she looks as good as
her bank account.
   She credits this to a change in lifestyle. She has quit smoking,
does light impact aerobics and has adopted a healthier diet.
   In ``Annie McGuire,'' Moore played a woman who works for the
Manhattan borough president, has a teen-age son and remarries a
structural engineer with a son and daughter. She has a mother
(Eileen Heckart) who's an ultra-liberal activist, and her new
husband (Denis Arndt) has a father (John Randolph) who's a staunch
conservative.
   The stories were a little different from the usual sitcom fare.
In one show she was held up by a man in a wheelchair, then felt
obligated to find him a job.
   In another, her husband admited to having had an affair with his
late wife's sister. Once, she had to clear her father-in-law's
reputation from an old accusation that food poisoning in his
restaurant cost Thomas E. Dewey the presidency.
   ``We're breaking a few molds,'' she says. ``We do some outlandish
things and conduct ourselves like adults having a great time.''
   It was Moore's first one-camera show without an audience since
she displayed only her legs as ``Sam'' on ``Richard Diamond, Private
Detective,'' in 1959.
</TEXT>
