<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-88 1240EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-YE--Theater'88 Adv00   12-14 0838</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-YE--Theater '88, Adv 00,0853</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release in Year-End Editions</NOTE>
<HEAD>Meager Year for Musicals; Several New Plays Flourished</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was a meager year for musicals, but a
half-dozen deserving new plays and several old ones managed to make
it to New York and flourish during 1988.
   ``The Phantom of the Opera'' was the year's biggest hit and its
best musical. Deservedly so. Andrew Lloyd Webber produced his most
accomplished score to date _ lush, romantic and sweeping music that
perfectly captured Gaston Leroux's passionate tale of love denied.
Michael Crawford was a heart-stopping and heart-breaking phantom,
Harold Prince's direction was impeccable, and Maria Bjornson
provided some eye-popping costumes and scenery.
   But after ``Phantom,'' which opened in January, nothing else
excited the musical theater for the rest of the year. There were
minor American musicals like the short-lived ``Mail'' and the two
one-act musicals about love operating under the title ``Romance
Romance.''
   The inevitable turkeys also took to the stage, particularly two
British gobblers, ``Carrie'' and ``Chess.''
   ``Carrie,'' in particular, signaled that the British musical
domination of Broadway was over. The show was an $8 million
disaster, Broadway's most expensive flop. It was based on the
Stephen King horror novel about a dumpy, awkward teen-age girl with
telekinetic powers. Betty Buckley and 16-year-old Linzi Hateley, in
the title role, sang their hearts out, but nothing could save this
dud.
   New York had better luck with plays, particularly new works by
American authors. Topping the list, and also taking the Tony award
as best play, was ``M. Butterfly,'' David Henry Hwang's brilliant
recreation of a spy scandal and love affair involving a French
diplomat and a Chinese opera singer who turns out to be a man. David
Dukes now plays the diplomat and gives such a compelling,
on-the-edge performance that the play seems even better than when it
first opened last March.
   Other notable new works by established playwrights included ``Joe
Turner's Come and Gone,'' August Wilson's story of the search for
identity among the children of slaves; Athol Fugard's ``The Road to
Mecca,'' a tale of one woman's determination to remain independent;
``Speed-the-Plow,'' David Mamet's scathing look at Hollywood greed
and glory, and ``The Cocktail Hour,'' A.R. Gurney's comic
examination of upper-class generational conflict.
   Lesser-known playwrights also had success. Off-Broadway's
``Reckless,'' by Craig Lucas, was a biting black comedy about a
woman's escape from her family after her husband announces he plans
to have her killed on Christmas Eve.
   Richard Greenberg's ``Eastern Standard'' offered another
fascinating evening. It opens on Broadway Jan. 5, direct from
off-Broadway's Manhattan Theater Club. The play follows several
yuppies as they try to grow up in New York during the late 1980s.
It's a witty, compassionate play about the most disliked group in
America.
   Several actors gave memorable performances this year.
   Among the best: B.D. Wong, whose gender switch in ``M.
Butterfly'' was nothing less than astonishing; Robin Bartlett, the
distraught wife in ``Reckless''; Yvonne Bryceland, the feisty,
independent sculptor in ``The Road to Mecca''; Ron Silver, oozing an
insincere charm as a smarmy would-be Hollywood producer in
``Speed-the-Plow,'' and Nancy Marchand as a diplomatic and wise WASP
matriarch in ``The Cocktail Hour.''
   But there were other performances that some actors might want to
erase from their Playbill biographies: Al Pacino, Martin Sheen and
Edward Herrmann massacring ``Julius Caesar'' in more ways than one;
Madonna, sleepwalking through her role in ``Speed-the-Plow''; and
Mariette Hartley coming to grief as a grief-stricken queen in
Shakespeare's rarely produced ``King John.''
   Most underrated performance: Sarah Brightman in ``The Phantom of
the Opera.'' Sure she isn't Sarah Bernhardt, but the woman has a
glorious, pristine voice that would be terrific to hear in some
classic musical comedy by Rodgers and Hart, Gershwin or Porter. And
Lloyd Webber wrote the role of Christine in ``Phantom'' for her. If
there's any doubt, listen to the singers who have followed her in
the New York cast. Not even close.
   Most overrated performances: Four of the five performers in the
revival of ``Ain't Misbehavin'.'' The show should have been called
``Are Misbehavin',' considering the extra histrionics _ vocal and
otherwise _ by Nell Carter, Ken Page, Armelia McQueen and Charlaine
Woodard. Only Andre De Shields managed to rein in the theatrics.
   The year produced three exceptional revivals: Peter Brook's spare
but satisfying version of Chekhov's ``The Cherry Orchard,'' done by
the Brooklyn Academy of Music at Brooklyn's Majestic Theater; Sean
O'Casey's ``Juno and the Paycock,'' in an atmospheric production
from the Gate Theater in Dublin; and the Lincoln Center Theater's
dark, brooding version of Thornton Wilder's ``Our Town.''
   Not hitting the mark was the year's most anticipated revival,
Samuel Beckett's ``Waiting for Godot,'' starring Steve Martin and
Robin Williams and directed by Mike Nichols at Lincoln Center. The
ticket demand was enormous. Most people, including some subscribers
to the Lincoln Center Theater, couldn't get in, but what they missed
was more post-modern burlesque than Beckett.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Year-End Editions</NOTE>
