<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-88 1245EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-YE--Trivia'88 Adv00-1stAdd   12-14 0809</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-YE--Trivia '88, Adv 00 - 1st Add,0840</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release in Year-End Editions</NOTE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: in Alaska.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   20. Racketeering indictments.
   21. The entire duration of Michael Spinks' consciousness in the
first round of his heavyweight championship bout with Mike Tyson.
   22. The entire duration of Mike Tyson's union with actress Robin
Givens. They married Feb. 7 after the NBA All-Star Game, replighted
their troths two days later, and she filed for divorce Oct. 7.
   23. Britain's first ski-jump competitor at the Winter Olympics in
50 years, Eddie Edwards finished dead last in the 70- and 90-meter
events but became a minor celebrity and made several commercial
endorsements.
   24. Track star Florence Griffith Joyner, noted for her Olympic
gold medals in the 100 and 200 meter races, and for her exotic
running togs.
   25. The Task Force on Market Mechanism, led by former Sen.
Nicholas Brady, which investigated the Crash of '87 and made
recommendations on market practices and procedures.
   26. The rebel, traditionalist archbishop was excommunicated by
the Roman Catholic Church for consecrating four bishops without
approval from the Vatican, threatening the first schism in
Catholicism in 118 years.
   27. The Dukakis campaign press plane, a 20-year-old Boeing 737
notorious for being unable to make a cross-country trip without
refueling.
   28. ``Tax Freedom Day,'' the last of 126 days the average
American had to work just to pay federal, state and local taxes in
1988. It came two days later than in 1987.
   29. Erika Schinegger of Austria won the 1966 women's downhill
skiing world championship at Portillo, Chile, but discovered later
in her career that she was a man. Schinegger, who is 40, married,
father of a small daughter and goes by the name of Erik, informally
gave the medal to runner-up Mariell Goitschel.
   30. The installment of the syndicated talk show ``Geraldo'' that
won Geraldo Rivera his highest ratings. In a televised melee, black
activist Roy Innis grabbed the neck of John Metzger, leader of the
White Aryan Resistance Youth, after Metzger called him an ``Uncle
Tom,'' and Rivera stopped a chair with his face, breaking his nose.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WHO SAID IT?
   
   A. Jimmy Swaggart, returning to preach his first sermon since
stepping down from the pulpit Feb. 21 after admitting to unspecified
sins but refusing to accept the discipline of his church.
   B. Gary Hart, announcing his second withdrawal from the race for
the Democratic presidential nomination.
   C. Ann Richards, Texas state treasurer, addressing the Democratic
National Convention and referring to George Bush.
   D. Art gallery proprietor David Spellerberg, after a judge
declared his $200,000 Rolls-Royce a public nuisance for hogging a
parking spot on the glitzy shopping street.
   E. New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, on Alton Maddox, C. Vernon Mason
and the Rev. Al Sharpton, three advisers to Tawana Brawley, a black
teen-ager who a grand jury concluded had lied about her alleged
abduction and rape by a gang of white men.
   
   F. Gov. Michael Dukakis, on his failure to win his nation's
highest office.
   G. Miss America, Gretchen Elizabeth Carlson, explaining that she
lost 20 pounds to get her 5-foot-3 frame down to a pert 108.
   H. Evan Mecham, after becoming the the first U.S. governor in 59
years to be impeached and stripped of his office.
   I. Timothy Leary, LSD guru of the '60s, on his decision to have
his head removed and frozen after he dies for possible resurrection.
   J. Sheelah Ryan, a 63-year-old real estate agent who won
Florida's single-winner U.S.-record $55 million Lotto jackpot.
   K. Mathias Rust, who spent 14 months in a Soviet jail for flying
a small plane into Red Square, on the positive influences of his
imprisonment.
   L. Mellissa L. Sanders, on the end of her record 516-day stay in
a shack atop two telephone poles to raise money for cancer research.
   M. DeAndra Anrig, 8, who took a 100-foot ride in the sky when an
airplane snagged her kite line and yanked her into the air.
   N. Vern Tejas, who became the first mountaineer to conquer Mount
McKinley alone in winter, referring to Naomi Uemura, the only other
person to successfully reach the 20,320-foot summit solo in winter
but who disappeared during his descent.
   
   O. Republican presidential candidate Pat Robertson, responding to
criticism that he is too militant in his stand against communism.
   P. Heavyweight champion Mike Tyson insisting that two police
officers take his new $183,000 Bentley convertible after he was
involved in a fender-bender in Manhattan. The cops' bosses made them
return it.
   Q. President Reag.... or rather, Larry Speakes, former Reagan
press aide. Speakes acknowledged after leaving the White House that
he had made up such quotes (this one at the Geneva summit) and
passed them along to reporters as the president's own. Reagan denied
it. Or, at least, so said his spokesman.
   

</TEXT>
