<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-88 2216EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-YE--Mysteries'88 Adv00   12-14 0917</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-YE--Mysteries '88, Adv 00,0943</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release in Year-End Editions</NOTE>
<HEAD>How Was Shroud Made? Where Are Whales Now? Who Were Those
Terrorists?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL CORMIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What finally became of Putu and Siku, those
celebrated whales? What is the truth about the Shroud of Turin? Who
bombed George Shultz's motorcade?
   As 1988 draws to a close, some nagging questions remain
unanswered:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE WHALES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   On Oct. 7, a hunter off Point Barrow, Alaska, discovered three
California gray whales trapped by early Arctic ice. In an expensive
international operation, Eskimos cut breathing holes for the whales
with chain saws, and two Soviet icebreakers cleared a channel for
the whales to start their trip back to open water. One of the whales
apparently died in the process.
   The weary survivors, dubbed Siku (Ice) and Putu (Ice Hole), faced
a swim to the open sea of 200 ice-clogged miles, to join 21,000
fellow grays migrating 5,000 miles to warmer waters off Mexico. The
whales haven't been seen again and are unlikely to be spotted, but
hope is high for their survival.
   ``They had the will to live,'' says rescue coordinator Ron
Morris. ``They should make it.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE SHROUD OF TURIN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Science heightened the mystery surrounding the Shroud of Turin
Oct. 13 when the Roman Catholic archbishop of Turin announced that,
according to lab tests, the cloth is no more than 728 years old and
cannot be the burial cloth of Christ.
   The linen strip, 14 feet, 3 inches long and 3 feet, 7 inches
wide, bears the faded image of a scourged and crucified man.
   Scientists say they have determined the shroud was not the
product of an artist, but do not know how the haunting image was
made. Those who believed it was Christ's burial cloth had attributed
the image to a sudden blaze of light, fitting Biblical accounts of
the resurrection. Others suspect radiation, or an unexplained
chemical reaction between body secretions and the cloth.
   The bishop, Anastasio Balestrero, says carbon-14 tests on tiny
samples date the cloth to between 1260 and 1390. Although critics
are now quick to brand the linen a medieval fake, the church says
the cloth continues to be a venerated symbol of faith, and the
mystery of its origin remains.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE SHULTZ ATTACK</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State Shultz escaped unharmed Aug. 8 when a bomb
exploded near his motorcade as he traveled to downtown La Paz,
Bolivia, from a nearby airport. The blast tore up pavement, damaged
three cars and blew out the car window next to Shultz's wife. No one
was hurt.
   Bolivian investigators said they believe a radical leftist group,
the Simon Bolivar Commando, was involved. Little is known about the
group, which claimed responsibility for targeting Shultz during his
10-day Latin American tour. The State Department was investigating
the attack but said it would not release its findings.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE CRUISE SHIP ATTACK</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   On July 11, terrorists fired guns and hurled grenades aboard the
Greek cruise ship City of Poros, killing nine people and injuring 98
other passengers returning from a day-long cruise on the Aegean Sea.
   The United States concluded that the Abu Nidal Palestinian group
probably mounted the attack, but the organization denied
responsibility. Anonymous callers claimed responsibility for a
variety of other groups.
   One theory was that the terrorists may have been seeking freedom
for Mohammed Rashid, a Palestinian jailed in Greece for entry on a
forged Syrian passport. Rashid is wanted by the United States on
charges he planted a bomb on a Pan Am jumbo jet in 1982 that killed
one person and injured 15.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE KUWAIT HIJACKING</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A Kuwaiti Airlines jumbo jet with 112 passengers and crew was
hijacked April 5 on a flight from Thailand to Kuwait and rerouted to
Iran and Cyprus. Two Kuwaitis were killed before the last hostages
were freed in Algeria as the 16-day ordeal reached a negotiated end.
   Western intelligence sources said the nine hijackers were
believed to be pro-Iranian Shiite Moslems of the Lebanon-based
Hezbollah, or Party of God. But the identities of the hijackers were
never revealed.
   One published report said the hijackers were flown from Algeria
to Syria and later reached Lebanon by land. There was no independent
confirmation, but one diplomat, insisting on anonymity, said, ``The
men are believed to have gone underground with Hezbollah in a
largely Shiite part of west Beirut where their trail is easily
lost.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE ZIA CRASH</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A Pakistani military plane crashed just after takeoff Aug. 17
near Bahawalpur, Pakistan, killing President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq,
U.S. Ambassador Arnold Raphel and 28 others. A Pakistani report shed
little light on who may have been responsible for what investigators
concluded was probably an act of sabotage.
   The report ruled out accidental technical failure aboard the
sturdy C-130 transport, and said investigators found no evidence of
an anti-aircraft missile or a powerful bomb. But investigators
discovered residues of chemicals that could be used in an explosive
strong enough to cause a technical malfunction. If it was sabotage,
suspects included agents of Soviet-allied Afghanistan, angered by
Zia's support for Afghan rebels; Pakistani ethnic or religious
minorities; or agents of India, which has fought three wars with
Pakistan. The Soviet Union and India have denied any involvement.
   Some published reports suggested that if the Soviet Union or
Afghanistan is implicated, neither Washington nor Islamabad will
want to make such charges public, in order to avoid a confrontation.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Year-End Editions</NOTE>
</DOC>
