<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   12-14 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0537</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retail sales in November got the crucial
holiday shopping season off to a fast start by posting a second
consecutive strong monthly gain, the government said.
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday that sales jumped 1.1
percent in November to a seasonally adjusted $138.1 billion. That
followed a 1.6 percent increase in October, revised upward from an
earlier estimate of 0.9 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The deficit in the broadest measure of U.S.
trade shrank to $30.89 billion from July through September, the
smallest imbalance in three years, the government reported.
   The Commerce Department reported Tuesday that the nation's
deficit in its current account narrowed by 8.4 percent after an 8.6
percent drop in the second quarter.
   Half the improvement in the third quarter came from a decline in
the merchandise trade deficit, which dropped to $28.5 billion,
reflecting a record level of U.S. exports.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. economy is likely to do better in 1989
than it has this year, because of growth in exports and capital
spending, the nation's purchasing managers said.
   Fifty-three percent of the purchasing managers surveyed felt
their businesses would be better in 1989 than in 1988, compared with
13 percent who expected it would be worse, the National Association
of Purchasing Management said Tuesday. The rest thought it would be
about the same.
   The report is based on a survey of purchasing executives in more
than 250 industrial companies in all 50 states.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumers became more cautious about their
economic futures in November following the presidential election and
the renewed debate over the budget deficit, a business-financed
research group reported.
   The Conference Board said Tuesday its Consumer Confidence Index
declined to 113.1 in November from a revised 116.9 in October.
   The monthly survey, which covers 5,000 U.S. households, indicated
that although consumers showed more confidence in present employment
conditions last month than in October, they turned less confident
about the outlook for the next six months.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of insolvent savings institutions
declined for the third consecutive quarter in the July-September
period, but even as government rescues soared other institutions
were slipping under water, regulators said.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board, which regulates federally
insured thrift associations, said Tuesday that 434 of 3,024 such
institutions were insolvent at the end of September, down from 498
three months earlier and substantially lower than the peak of 520 at
the end of last year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pentagon auditors will expand a review of top
military contractors that already has found U.S. taxpayers are being
billed for millions of dollars in questionable consulting fees,
officials said.
   The first investigation covered a dozen contractors, but the new
review will look at 18 more over the next 10 weeks, William Reed,
director of the Defense Contract Audit Agency, said Tuesday.
   The review was ordered by Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci in
the wake of the Justice Department's ongoing investigation of
possible fraud and bribery involving defense contractors.
</TEXT>
