<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Occupational Health and Safety
Administration proposed fining a Pepperidge Farm Inc. plant nearly
$1.4 million for exposing workers to dangerous working conditions.
   The $1.384 million fine will be imposed if Pepperidge Farm does
not contest it within 15 working days, Jack Hord, spokesman in
Philadelphia for OSHA, an arm of the U.S. Department of Labor, said
Tuesday.
   The Norwalk, Conn.-based company said the fine was ``arbitrarily
assigned and totally unjustified'' and said it would contest the
alleged violations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financier Carl C. Icahn stoked the smoldering
takeover speculation about Texaco Inc., disclosing he had raised his
stake in the nation's third-largest oil company to 15.8 percent.
   Securities analysts said Tuesday that Icahn's move, which helped
boost Texaco's stock price, evidently reflected his impatience at
the pace of the company's post-bankruptcy restructuring aimed at
increasing the value of Texaco stock.
   Some said Icahn, Texaco's largest shareholder, probably had no
interest in acquiring the company himself but might be attempting to
induce another investor to make an offer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although the Premier ``smokeless'' cigarette is
drawing less than rave reviews from some smokers and retailers, RJR
Nabisco Inc. is not ready to scrap a two-state test of the product's
popularity.
   Despite consumer complaints about everything from the cigarette's
taste and smell to its price and unusual construction, RJR claims
Premier had the highest initial trial rate of any brand in recent
history.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. has cut its
involvement in the phone gear business, announcing plans to sell
part of its money-losing Rolm operation to West Germany's Siemens AG
and put the rest of Rolm into a joint venture with Siemens.
   The purchase announced Tuesday would make Siemens the world's
biggest seller of office phone switches.
   The price Siemens was paying was not disclosed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coca-Cola Co. and Pepsi-Cola Co. increased their
shares of the U.S. soft drink business this year, outpacing the
industry's 4.5 percent growth, an industry analyst said.
   Coca-Cola Classic, meanwhile, remained atop the list of the
best-selling soft drinks in the United States, according to Jesse
Meyers, publisher of the newsletter Beverage Digest.
   Beverage Digest said Coca-Cola's entire line of products captured
40.5 percent of the U.S. soft drink market this year, up from 40.3
percent last year. The Pepsi-Cola line increased to 30.7 percent
from 30.2 percent.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A late surge in blue-chip issues left the stock market narrowly
mixed Tuesday amid worries about the course of interest rates. The
Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which lost 3.91 points on
Monday, made it all back on Tuesday, gaining 3.91 to close at
2,143.49.
   The dollar rose amid year-end demand for the currency.
   Bond prices fell on disappointment over the government's retail
sales report.
   Copper futures prices plunged; precious metals edged lower;
cotton futures were sharply lower; energy futures declined; grains
and soybeans were mixed; livestock and meat were mixed; and
stock-index futures gained.
</TEXT>
