<1ST_LINE>r f PM-HolidayTravel Bjt   12-14 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Holiday Travel, Bjt,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More People Traveling By Bus, Train, Plane This Season</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOROTHY GAST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If projections by the nation's train, air and
bus lines are any indication, more Americans than ever will be
traveling during the Christmas and New Year's holidays in 1988.
   Greyhound, the nation's largest intercity bus line, says it will
carry 1.34 million passengers between Dec. 18 and Jan. 3, or 10
percent more than the 1.2 million people transported during the
holidays last year.
   In part, the bus line attributes the increase to a recent boost
in air fares and the limited availability of discount-priced seats
on the nation's major airlines, said Greyhound Chief Executive
Officer Fred G. Currey, who was in Cleveland on Tuesday to meet with
company employees.
   ``Airplane ticket prices are very substantially higher this year,
and they are a factor,'' Currey told reporters. ``And bus fares are
very moderately priced.''
   Currey's contention was disputed by organizations representing
airlines and the nation's travel agents.
   ``Most people buying at Christmas bought their tickets weeks and
months ago before fares went up,'' said Philip G. Davidoff,
president of Belair Travel of Bowie, Md., president-elect of the
travel agents' group.
   ``What's going to happen next year, I don't know. If the
increases are put into effect for January, it probably will mean
more people will take buses than ever before.''
   Bill Horn, a spokesman for the Air Transport Association, which
represents the nation's largest airlines, said a record 7 million
Americans traveled by air during the Thanksgiving holiday weekend.
   Between Dec. 17 and Jan. 2, U.S. airlines expect to transport at
least 22 million people, or about 500,000 more than for the same
period last year, he said. That would also be a record, Horn said.
   The nation's major airlines announced last month that they were
boosting most of their lowest discount fares and eliminating the
cheap fares that can be booked a few days before a flight. But a
week later, Eastern, Continental, Delta, and Northwest airlines
announced reductions in some of their fares.
   ``Those fare increases that were announced just prior to
Thanksgiving affected a very small percentage of the travel
market,'' Horn said in a telephone interview.
   Clifford Black, public relations manager for the National
Railroad Passenger Corp., better known as Amtrak, said the railroad
carried a record number of passengers in the fiscal year that ended
Sept. 30 and ``it shows no signs of letting up.''
   But limited capacity makes it difficult for the railroad to set
holiday records, he said.
   ``During the holiday seasons, they tend to sell out, making it
impossible to improve from year to year and from one holiday season
to the next,'' Black said.
   Denny Yatteau, Greyhound regional manager in Ohio, said he
expects 38,300 Greyhound tickets to be sold in the state for the
Christmas-New Year's season. That would be an increase of 12 percent
over a year ago.
   Black said space is limited on most Amtrak trains traveling from
Cleveland, Canton and Cincinnati this holiday season. Amtrak trains
traveling from Cleveland to Boston on Dec. 23 already are sold out,
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881214-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-88 0031EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SkiSeason Bjt   12-14 0850</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ski Season, Bjt,0873</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Massive Expansion Marks Start of Eastern Ski Season</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inspired by better snowmaking technology and
growing attendance, ski resorts in the Northeast are spending
millions of dollars in what industry officials call the region's
greatest expansion since the 1960s.
   The smaller, forested slopes of New England, New York and
Pennsylvania also have embarked on a marketing campaign designed to
persuade skiers that skiing here is just as good as in the wide-open
slopes of the Rockies.
   ``The weather's been good and snow conditions have been
favorable,'' said Cal Conniff, president of the National Ski Areas
Association, based in Springfield, Mass. ``As a result, New England
ski-area operators have been plowing quite a bit of money into new
equipment.''
   In the country's largest skiing development project this year,
Waterville Valley in New Hampshire is spending $30 million to make
the resort set 10 miles inside a national forest the ``Aspen of the
East.''
   Waterville is adding restaurants, boutiques, tennis courts and a
high-speed detachable chair lift that cuts the trip to the top of
the mountain in half. It has 30 new acres of slopes and snowmaking
equipment to cover 96 percent of the trails.
   ``It's really an economic window of opportunity,'' said Gary
Kiedaisch, Waterville Valley's vice president. ``We've always had a
pent-up market but we wanted more capacity. We were often maxed out
in our capacity.''
   In other recent developments:
   _Stratton Mountain in Vermont spent $4.5 million to install the
largest ski lift in the country, a 12-passenger gondola able to
carry 2,400 people an hour.
   _Burke Mountain in East Burke, Vt., is making more than $1
million in improvements to the 25-year-old ski area, including
construction of 100 condominiums and a 20 percent expansion of
snowmaking capabilities.
   _Shawnee Peak in Bridgton, Maine, is spending about $1.2 million
to stimulate a money-losing operation by adding new lifts, rental
equipment, more lodge space and lights that will make it the largest
night skiing resort in New England.
   _After a $1.5 million overhaul, Ski Adventure in Ashby, Mass., is
expected to reopen in December, six years after the old Mount
Watatic ski area went bankrupt and closed.
   The 185 ski areas in the Northeast led the nation in expansion
this year, spending $60.9 million on improvements, compared with $56
million spent by Rocky Mountain resorts and $51 million in Far West
ski areas, according to the National Ski Areas Association. In 1987,
Northeast ski areas spent $92.1 million, 2{ times the 1985 level.
   Last year, the eight states in the Northeast reported about 15
million skier visits, compared with 17 million in the Rockies. In
the 1984-85 season, attendance was less than 12 million in the East.
   The East has a basic topographic disadvantage because its tallest
mountains are less than half the size of the 10,000- to 12,000-foot
peaks found in the Rockies. Mount Washington in New Hampshire is the
region's tallest mountain at 6,200 feet.
   The Rockies also offer complete resort areas with open skiing in
wide, snowy fields. In New England, most trails are cut through
woods and ski areas are typically limited to lodges and have few
other recreational opportunities.
   To meet the competition, New England skiing associations have
expanded on a national campaign _ ``Let's Go Skiing America'' _ by
pushing for vacations at local resorts and trying to broaden modest
increases in attendance over the last two years.
   ``It's not because they're losing market share to the Caribbean
or some non-ski service,'' said Phil Camp, executive director of the
New England Ski Areas Council, an industry group. ``The rate of
growth of the consumer market in skiing has not been rapid like it
was 15 or 18 years ago.''
   In Vermont, ski areas are teaming up to make the state's resorts
a destination. One new program allows interchangable lift tickets at
Smugglers, Jay Peak, Bolton and Sugarbush.
   The Vermont Ski Areas Association this year also began
coordinating fly-drive packages from Washington, Baltimore and
Philadelphia to build on the state's traditional bases of Boston and
New York.
   More man-made snow is being poured on slopes earlier than ever. A
2-year-old Eastman Kodak Inc. product called Snomax allows snow to
be made at temperatures 4 degrees to 8 degrees warmer than before,
as high as freezing.
   Thanks to more sophisticated snowmaking, Camp said more than 50
of the 72 public ski areas in the six-state New England region were
open last weekend, a ``quantum leap'' over previous years.
   Said Conniff: ``The technology that's come along has taken a lot
of the risk out of the business in the last three or four years.''
   The onset of cold weather also has encouraged area ski officials
hopeful that single-digit temperatures will persuade city dwellers
to head for the slopes.
   ``The most important thing this cold weather has given us is an
unprecedented jump on snowmaking efforts,'' said David Zemel,
general manager of the Powder Ridge Ski Resort in Middlefield, Conn.
``More slopes are opening faster than I've ever seen in the seven
years I've been here.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881214-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-88 0032EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Texaco-Icahn Bjt   12-14 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texaco-Icahn, Bjt,0674</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Icahn Boosts Stake in Texaco</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. is facing renewed pressure from
financier Carl C. Icahn, who has raised his stake in the
third-biggest U.S. oil company and hasn't discouraged speculation he
might resurrect a failed takeover bid.
   Icahn stoked the smoldering takeover speculation about Texaco on
Tuesday, disclosing he had increased his stock ownership to 15.8
percent of the company's 240 million shares outstanding.
   Securities analysts said Icahn's move, which helped boost
Texaco's stock price, evidently reflected his impatience at the pace
of the company's post-bankruptcy restructuring aimed at increasing
the value of Texaco stock.
   Some said Icahn, Texaco's largest shareholder, probably had no
interest in acquiring the company himself but might be attempting to
induce another investor to make an offer.
   ``I think ultimately he's looking for a way to cash in,'' said
George Gaspar, who follows Texaco for the Milwaukee-based investment
firm Robert W. Baird & Co. ``I think he's trying to stir up the pond
and attract some outside interest to take a look at Texaco.''
   Others did not rule out the possibility of a takeover attempt by
Icahn, who began acquiring Texaco stock while the company was under
federal bankruptcy court protection a year ago.
   Icahn declined to comment on why he raised his stake. Texaco
officials also declined to comment.
   Texaco stock rose 87{ cents a share Tuesday to $51.62{ in heavy
trading on the New York Stock Exchange, an indication that investors
believe either Icahn or someone else may try to win control of the
company.
   Last spring, Icahn made an offer for Texaco valued at $14.5
billion, or $60 a share, as part of a shareholder proxy fight to
oust the company's board. But his strategy was defeated by
shareholders loyal to the board, which promised to boost Texaco's
stock price through an aggressive restructuring.
   But since then, Texaco stock has not risen significantly, raising
the possibility that more shareholders would align themselves with
Icahn if he undertook another takeover attempt. Moreover, some
analysts said, the idea that Icahn could raise the financing for
such a takeover is not far-fetched.
   ``Last spring, nobody believed anybody could raise $14 or $15
billion for an acquisition,'' said Jack N. Aydin, an oil securities
analyst at the Cleveland-based investment firm McDonald & Co. ``This
year it's different.''
   The most notable example is the record $24.53 billion acquisition
of RJR Nabisco Inc. by the buyout firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co.
announced less than two weeks ago.
   Icahn said in a filing with the Securities and Exchange
Commission that he purchased 2.6 million shares of Texaco between
Dec. 7 and Dec. 12 for about $131 million, or an average of $50.37{
a share.
   Some Texaco analysts and takeover attorneys thought Icahn's move
signaled he was not interested in buying the company, because it
vaulted his stake over a 15 percent threshold that under some
circumstances triggers the anti-takeover laws of Delaware, where
Texaco is incorporated.
   Icahn would have to immediately raise his ownership to 85 percent
or wait at least three years before attempting any hostile
acquisition that would result in the company's breakup, attorneys
familiar with the Delaware law said.
   His latest move came against a background of resurgent rumors
that he was growing exasperated with Texaco's multibillion dollar
asset-shedding program and the company's failure to specify the date
of a promised $1.7 billion distribution to shareholders.
   Icahn is chairman of Trans World Airlines Inc., one of his
successful acquisitions. He widely is regarded as a shrewd financier
and takeover investor and has gone after some of the biggest U.S.
corporations, such as USX Corp. and Phillips Petroleum Co.
   He has been a thorn in the side of Texaco management, which has
been preoccupied with restructuring the company since it emerged
from bankruptcy protection several months ago after settling a
multibillion dollar dispute with Pennzoil Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881214-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-88 0034EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-IBM-Rolm Bjt   12-14 0760</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-IBM-Rolm, Bjt,0782</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IBM Announces Rolm Sale-Venture With Germany's Siemens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. is reducing
its role in the telecommunications equipment business by selling
part of its money-losing Rolm operation to West Germany's Siemens AG
and putting the rest of Rolm into a joint venture with Siemens.
   The deal announced Tuesday marks another chapter in IBM's mixed
success with Rolm, a freewheeling Silicon Valley company that the
computer giant bought four years ago for an estimated $1.5 billion
to help it link computers through phone switches.
   Rolm is believed to have lost hundreds of millions of dollars in
recent years, but has grown into the nation's biggest seller of
office phone switches _ which route calls within buildings _ under
IBM's ownership.
   The purchase would make Siemens the world's biggest seller of
office phone switches. Siemens could consolidate its lead if it
manages to buy Italtel, an Italian phone company, and Britain's
Plessey Co., for which it is making a $3.1 billion hostile offer in
cooperation with Britain's General Electric Co.
   The price Siemens is paying was not disclosed, but IBM said the
deal would have no material effect on its income statement when it
is completed early next year. That was taken as positive news for
IBM, because there had been speculation the sale price would be so
low that IBM would be forced to take a large writeoff.
   John F. Akers, IBM's chairman and chief executive, said, ``I
would absolutely not characterize it as a scaling back of IBM's
interests in telecommunications.'' He said the combination with
Siemens would allow IBM to offer a wider range of products to its
customers than before.
   But analysts said IBM is turning over all responsibility for
development and manufacture of Rolm-branded products to Siemens and
is discontinuing work on a complex office switch for the European
market.
   ``For IBM, it's a very clean market exit,'' said Francis
McInerney of Northern Business Information-Datapro in New York.
   ``It is a graceful but not total retreat, no matter how you cut
it,'' said Frank Barbetta, a researcher for Probe Research Inc. in
Cedar Knolls, N.J.
   IBM will sell the development and manufacturing arm of Rolm, with
its 2,800 employees, to Siemens. It will become Rolm Systems Inc.
and include 700 employees now working for Siemens.
   IBM and Siemens jointly will own a marketing and services
company, known simply as Rolm, that will offer telecommunications
products for private networks in the United States. It will have
5,500 employees who currently work for Rolm and fewer than 100 now
working for Siemens.
   IBM gradually will phase out a Rolm manufacturing and development
plant in Colorado Springs, Colo., and offer jobs elsewhere in the
company to the 550 affect employees. Those who do not accept
transfers will be offered severance packages.
   Under IBM's ownership, Rolm has lost money steadily, but its
share of the U.S. market has risen to 18.1 percent from 14.2 percent
in 1984, according to Northern Business Information-Datapro.
   IBM had bought Rolm as insurance in case the trend in computers
was to connect them through office phone switches, according to
Kenneth Bosomworth, president of International Resource Development
Inc. of New Canaan, Conn. Instead, most office computers are
connected through special local area networks, an area in which IBM
is also strong.
   Rolm was vulnerable to competition because it does not make
switches for the central offices of phone companies, in contrast to
competitors such as American Telephone & Telegraph Co. and Canada's
Northern Telecom Ltd., Bosomworth said.
   Siemens does make central office switches. Phone networks are
being redesigned to handle computer data and video signals as well
as voice traffic, and companies that make central office switches
are at the cutting edge of work in the field, Bosomworth said.
   In a sign of the importance the companies attached to the deal,
it was announced jointly at a news conference by Akers, who rarely
appears at press conferences, and Karlheinz Kaske, president and
chief executive of Siemens.
   Rolm has development and manufacturing operations in Santa Clara,
Calif., and Austin, Texas. Siemens has telecommunications
development operations in Boca Raton, Fla., and manufacturing in
Cherry Hill, N.J.
   The companies said Rolm Systems Inc. would be headquartered in
Santa Clara, and would be expanded to include about 700 Siemens
employees based in Boca Raton and Cherry Hill.
   Rolm, the marketing company, will be based in the Stamford,
Conn., area and will include fewer than 100 people now working for
Siemens in addition to the IBM employees.
</TEXT>
