<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-StockScandal 1stLd-Writethru f0316HockeyLeague
12-14 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Stock Scandal, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0316-0317,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>NTT Chairman Latest Victim of Japanese Stock Scandal</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: NEW grafs 1-5 to UPDATE with Shinto's resignation; picks up
6th graf pvs bg'ng, The so-called ...; Combines pvs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Co.,
the world's biggest company, resigned Wednesday under fire for
alleged involvement in a scandal that has spread wide tentacles
through Japan's political and business world.
   The minister of posts and telecommunications, Masaaki Nakayama,
told a news conference he had accepted the resignation of Hisashi
Shinto as NTT chairman.
   Nakayama said Shinto had denied any personal involvement in
dubious share trading but had accepted responsibility for actions by
his personal secretary.
   Japanese press reports said prosecutors had traced some 10
million Japanese yen, or around $81,000, to Shinto's bank account
from proceeds of the sale of shares in Recruit-Cosmos Co., a real
estate subsidiary of the Recruit conglomerate.
   Shinto on Tuesday had issued a statement denying involvement in
the share transaction, which was carried out by his personal
secretary, Kozo Murata, in 1986. Murata has since resigned as
Shinto's aide.
   The so-called Recruit scandal last week brought the resignation
of Kiichi Miyazawa as finance minister and deputy prime minister,
and has rocked the Japanese political and business worlds with
allegations that the Recruit company was seeking favors by
distributing shares in Recruit-Cosmos with a guarantee of easy,
tax-free profits.
   NTT, ranked as the largest corporation in the world in terms of
stock market capitalization, had business links with Recruit, which
bought two U.S.-made supercomputers from NTT and leased data
communications circuits from the telephone giant.
   As a former telecommunications monopoly, NTT has been partially
privatized, but Shinto and all other officials of the utility remain
under regulations which make it illegal for them to receive cash or
shares from private companies that NTT does business with.
   Shinto has been the chief executive of the telecommunications
giant since 1981, when NTT was still a government-owned monopoly. He
oversaw the privatization, which started in 1985, and then took the
title of president. He held that post until last June, when he
became chairman and chief executive, and the title of president went
to Haruo Yamaguchi.
   Shinto's resignation would make him the most prominent victim in
the business world of the Recruit scandal, which has also brought
the resignation of news media executives and has broken several
political careers in addition to that of Miyazawa, who a year ago
was a major contender to be prime minister.
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita is on a list of prominent
politicians whose aides profited from owning Recruit-Cosmos shares,
but he and the others denied any knowledge or involvement in the
transactions. Among the others are former Prime Minister Yasuhiro
Nakasone and Shintaro Abe, secretary-general of the governing
Liberal Democratic Party.
   The roots of the scandal go back to 1986 when unlisted
Recruit-Cosmos shares were offered to the prominent figures or their
aides, often to be paid for with loans from a Recruit-linked finance
company. The shares were listed for sale in the over-the-counter
market in October 1986 and immediately skyrocketed in value,
yielding tax-free profits when they were sold.
</TEXT>
