<2ND_LINE>AM-New Cable,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Trans-Atlantic Cable Will Increase Phone Capacity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first fiber-optic telephone cable across the
Atlantic goes into service Wednesday, greatly increasing the number
of calls that can be placed to Europe at one time, according to a
published report.
   The New York Times, in Wednesday's editions, says the new cable
can carry 40,000 calls simultaneously by using pulses of laser light
to send voice and computer data.
   The three existing trans-Atlantic cables, made of copper, along
with satellites, can carry a total of 20,000 calls, the Times noted.
   The new cable was installed over six months at a cost of $362
million and illustrates the increasing pace with which
communications companies are stringing fiber-optic cables along the
ocean floor and across North America, Europe, Asia and Australia.
   The cable is a joint venture of 29 European and North American
telephone companies, including American Telephone & Telegraph Co.,
ITT Corp., British Telecommunications PLC, France Telcom and Western
Union. AT&T, which installed the cable, will also operate it.
</TEXT>
