<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     12-14 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched up against the Japanese yen today,
while share prices rebounded on the Tokyo Stock Exchange amid
optimism about an impending U.S. trade report, dealers said.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which dropped 74.48 points
Tuesday, gained 156.92 points, or 0.53 percent, finishing at
29,754.73.
   The rebound followed the dollar's firming on the currency market
as traders anticipated a narrowing of the U.S. trade deficit for
October, said a dealer with Nomura Securities, Japan's largest
brokerage.
   ``The dollar's uptrend encouraged stock investors to buy
export-related issues such as Sony and Matsushita,'' said the
dealer, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He said the same optimism first had pushed up the dollar on the
currency market, prompting the Nikkei to rise.
   ``Investors are now expecting the U.S. trade deficit to shrink to
about $9.5 billion,'' he added. September's U.S. deficit was $10.46
billion.
   The U.S. Commerce Department was to release the nation's trade
figures for October later Wednesday.
   Volume traded on the first section was estimated at 1 billion
shares.
   On the currency exchange market, the dollar closed unchanged from
the opening at 123.35 yen, up 0.29 yen from Tuesday's close of
123.06 yen. The currency moved in a tight range of 123.25-123.45 yen.
   A Mitsubishi Bank dealer said a majority of traders remained on
the sidelines to await the U.S. trade report.
   ``The dollar-yen rate today was barely moving in a cautious
mood,'' he said, adding that there was no other news to affect
market trends.
   If the U.S. trade deficit matches market expectations of about
$10 billion, the dollar-yen rate is unlikely to change soon from the
current level, he said.
</TEXT>
