<1ST_LINE>d f PM-MonitorEditors     12-14 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Monitor Editors,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Christian Monitor Editors Named</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Curtis J. Sitomer, who has spent 20 years with The
Christian Science Monitor, has been appointed managing editor of the
80-year-old daily newspaper.
   Monitor Editor Richard J. Cattani on Tuesday also announced four
other key editorial appointments created by the recent resignations
of Editor Katherine Fanning and others over policy differences with
management.
   Cattani also said plans are under way to introduce a new design
and format at the newspaper in early 1989.
   Sitomer most recently was a senior columnist writing on justice,
religion and law. He also held several other Monitor positions,
including special sections editor, American news editor and Los
Angeles bureau chief.
   The other appointments are Ruth Walker, former assistant
editorial page editor, as assistant managing editor; Brad
Knickerbocker, former national news editor, as editorial page
editor; Peter N. Spotts, former editorial writer, as national news
editor; and Keith Henderson, former editorial writer, as assistant
editorial page editor.
</TEXT>
