<1ST_LINE>r f PM-DroughtInsurance     12-14 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought Insurance,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chubb Reaches Settlement With Illinois Over Drought Insurance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Illinois has dropped administrative
charges against Chubb Corp. over the sale of drought insurance after
the New Jersey company agreed to pay a $50,000 fine and the $100,000
cost of a state probe.
   State Insurance Director John Washburn announced the action
Tuesday, four days after a federal judge in Cincinnati approved a
$48 million drought insurance settlement for 8,800 farmers in 10
states, including Illinois.
   ``Chubb has acted very responsibly in agreeing to settle this
entire issue in such an expeditious manner,'' Washburn said.
   ``As a result, the department's goal of obtaining coverage for
all of the farmers who applied for this coverage was achieved, and
we resolved our administrative proceedings and concluded this matter
at no expense to Illinois taxpayers,'' he said.
   Federal Insurance Co., a subsidiary of Chubb, was cited for nine
violations of Illinois law in administrative charges filed in
October.
   The company was accused of selling insurance against inadequate
rain to farmers who thought they were buying coverage for
drought-related crop losses. The policy is not allowed by state law.
</TEXT>
