<DOCNO> AP881214-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-88 0847EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Belgium-Banking     12-14 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Belgium-Banking,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Belgium Raises All Banking Rates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Belgium's central bank boosted all key
banking interest rates by 0.25 percentage points Wednesday,
reflecting the growing trend toward higher rates in the
international markets.
   The Belgian National Bank Wednesday said the discount rate was
raised to 7.5 percent and the Lombard rate to 7.75 percent.
   The discount rate is the interest the central bank charges on
loans to member commercial banks.The Lombard rate is what the banks
are charged for supplemental borrowings in which securities are used
as collateral.
   The National Bank had announced earlier it was raising one-, two-
and three-month treasury bills.
   The three-month rate, considered the most important in Belgian
banking, was raised to 7.4 percent from 7.15 percent, the one-month
rate to 7.35 from 7.1 percent and the two-month rate to 7.4 from
7.15 percent.
   All the moves take effect on Thursday.
   The National Bank said the rate changes came ``in recognition of
the recent evolution of interest rates on the international
markets.''
   Short-term rate levels have been rising in recent weeks in many
industrial countries, prompting speculation that both the West
German Bundesbank and the U.S. Federal Reserve might raise key rates
soon.
   Strong economic growth in major industrialized countries has
given rise to fears of a resurgence of inflation in many quarters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
