<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru,0340</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with dollar falling against many currencies on trade
report</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell against many major currencies
in Europe this afternoon after the U.S. government announced that
the trade deficit for October was only slightly better than many
economists had expected.
   The dollar, which had been mixed in light trading ahead of the
1:30 p.m. release of the trade report, dipped after the Commerce
Department announced that the deficit narrowed to $10.35 billion in
October, the smallest imbalance in three months, from a revised
September deficit of $10.67 billion.
   Market expectations for the trade deficit had varied widely, from
$12 billion to as low as $8.5 billion, but many economists had
expected the deficit to roughly match September's.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.8250 after the report was
released from $1.8195 at midmorning. But it was stll lower than
$1.8280 Wednesday.
   Other dollar rates after the trade report, with midmorning rates
in parentheses, as compared with late Wednesday's rates, were:
1.7413 (1.7483) West German marks, up from 1.7410; 1.4670 (1.4700)
Swiss francs, down from 1.4705; 5.9525 (5.9765) French francs, down
from 5.9775; 1.9675 (1.9552) Dutch guilders, down from 1.9715;
1,285.50 (1,287.80) Italian lire, down from 1,286.50; 1.2005
(1.2020) Canadian dollars, up from 1.1995.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.29 yen to a closing 123.35. Later in London, it
was quoted at 122.75 yen after the report and 123.35 yen before.
   London's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price for
gold of $419.60 a troy ounce at midmorning Wednesday, unchanged from
the opening bid but slightly lower than $420.75 bid late Tuesday.
   The bid price for gold was also $419.60 an ounce in Zurich, down
from $420.45 bid late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 16 cents to close at a bid
$421.38.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid $6.15 a troy ounce, down
from Tuesday's $6.17.
</TEXT>
