<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru f0046 12-14 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0046,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>November Retail Sales Jump, Raising Concerns About Inflation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, The dollar ..., with UPDATE on trading.
INSERTS New grafs 6-7, In another ... in October, to UPDATE with
industrial production and capacity utilization for November. Picks
up 6th graf pvs, On Tuesday ... Will be led with report on business
inventories for October after 10 a.m. EST release.
^By PETER COY</NOTE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. trade deficit declined to $10.35 billion in October, the
smallest imbalance in three months, the government reported today.
   The Commerce Department said the merchandise trade gap between
what the United States imports and what it sells overseas fell by
3.1 percent from a September deficit of $10.67 billion.
   The decline, the second consecutive improvement, was slightly
better than many economists had been predicting.
   The dollar and bond prices were lower following today's
announcement.
   The October improvement came from a 1.7 percent drop in imports,
which declined to $38.02 billion, on a seasonally adjusted basis.
This decline offset a smaller 1.1 percent drop in U.S. exports,
which edged down to $11.75 billion.
   In another report today, the Federal Reserve Board said the use
of industrial capacity rose 0.2 percentage points to 84.2 percent
last month, the highest level since 84.3 percent in November 1979.
It was the seventh increase in eight months.
   An accompanying Fed report said industrial production climbed a
brisk 0.5 percent in November following an identical 0.5 percent
rise in October.
   On Tuesday, the government reported that November retail sales
jumped 1.1 percent, giving rise to more worries about inflation
while giving store owners more confidence about the outlook for the
holiday shopping season.
   ``It looks like the Christmas season will be better than people
feared and make an important contribution to growth,'' Commerce
Undersecretary Robert Ortner said Tuesday in releasing the report.
   Christmas sales provide general merchandisers with about half of
their annual profits. Retail sales are considered a key indicator of
economic growth because consumer activity accounts for about
two-thirds of gross national product.
   In other economic developments Tuesday:
   _The Commerce Department said the deficit in the broadest measure
of U.S. trade shrank to $30.89 billion from July through September,
the smallest imbalance in three years.
   _The Conference Board, a business-financed research group,
indicated consumers became more cautious about their economic
futures in November following the presidential election and the
renewed debate over the budget deficit.
   _The National Association of Purchasing Management said its
members expect the economy to do better in 1989 than it has done
this year, with continued growth and slower inflation.
   Bond prices fell on Tuesday in reaction to the concerns about
inflation raised by the retail sales report. The yield on the
Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond, which rises when the price falls,
edged up to 8.97 percent from 8.95 percent late Monday.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which
lost 3.91 points on Monday, closed up 3.91 on Tuesday at 2,143.49.
Broader indicators of the market narrowly declined.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
