<DOCNO> AP881214-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-88 1018EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Nigeria-Airline     12-14 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Nigeria-Airline,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Airline Sacks 3,000 Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nigeria Airways has dismissed 3,000
workers, a third of the work force, in a bid to keep the bankrupt
airline operating.
   Police surrounded the state airline's headquarters on Wednesday
to prevent attacks.
   Earlier this year, the airline sharply reduced its overseas
flights after accidents grounded some aircraft and two planes were
seized for non-payment of debts. Nigeria Airways has been denied
overflight rights by some countries for refusing to pay its bills.
   The airline reportedly owes creditors more than $1 billion.
   International flight attendants were replaced with attendants
from domestic flights this year after several attendants and flight
crew members were arrested on drugs charges in the United States,
Europe and Britain.
   Some senior officials were among those dismissed Wednesday,
including the director of engineering and maintenance.
   Retired Maj. Gen. Olu Bajowa, who was appointed administrator to
resolve the airline's financial problems, announced the dismissals.
   In addition to management problems, the airline suffered through
years of over-valuation of the Nigerian naira and its fares, set by
the government, which often were below cost.
   Some officials of the military government have predicted the
airline would be privatized.
   Last month, Bajowa ordered the airline to change the symbol on
its planes' tail sections from a flying elephant to an eagle.
</TEXT>
