<1ST_LINE>r f BC-WorldWheat     12-14 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-World Wheat,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wheat Production Could Reach New Levels, Council Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World wheat production could reach a record 550
million metric tons in the 1989-90 season, the International Wheat
Council said Wednesday.
   This would be 5 million tons more than expected consumption and
would allow world stocks to rebuild, said the council, the
commodity's leading forecasting body.
   A decline in stocks after the estimated fall of 37 million tons
this season would leave an ``uncomfortably narrow margin of security
between world supply and demand,'' the council said.
   Stocks built up during the wheat glut of the mid-1980s are being
depleted this season because of the sharp drop in 1988-89 wheat
production caused by droughts in the United States and Canada.
   World wheat production for 1988-89 now is forecast by the council
at 500 million tons, 13 million below the previous season's figure
and 37 million down on the 1986-87 record.
   Tighter supplies this season have led to higher world prices
which are encouraging growers to increase plantings for 1989-90, the
council said.
   World production of coarse grains, principally corn, now is
estimated at 718 million tons for 1988-89, compared with 712 million
forecast in October and the 1987-88 output of 804 million, the
council said.
   The council has raised by 2 million tons to 33 million tons its
estimate of 1988-89 Soviet grain import needs. That's up from 32
million tons in 1987-88. Its estimates of Soviet wheat production
remained unchanged at 200 million tons compared with 211 million in
1987-88.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
