<HEAD>Sears Plans Should Bring At Least 1,400 Full-Time Jobs To
Louisville</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plans by Sears, Roebuck & Co. for new
credit and catalog centers are expected to create at least 1,400
full-time jobs here, officials said.
   A credit-operations center will employ 600 to 700 people, while a
catalog-ordering center will employ about 800 full-time workers and
as many as 400 others part time during busy seasons, Louisville
officials said Tuesday.
   Jefferson County Judge-Executive Harvey Sloane said the county
will provide $250,000 in incentive money for the credit center, with
the county to recover the funds through increased occupational-tax
revenue.
   Becky Brown, Sloane's press secretary, said Tuesday that the
county also is discussing possible assistance for the catalog center.
   ``We've been working with Sears for months,'' Sloane said. ``This
is a major commitment by the No. 1 retailer in the world to
Jefferson County.''
   The credit operation will screen new applications for Sears
credit cards and review changes in credit limits for existing card
holders.
   The local operation will be separate from the Sears Discover
Card, which has a clearinghouse operation in Columbus, Ohio.
   NTS Inc. has a signed lease for Sears to open the credit center
at its Crossings project in eastern Jefferson County, said NTS
executive Burt Deutsch.
   Silliman Development Co. confirmed Tuesday that it has a signed
lease for Sears to open the catalog center at its Hunnington Park
project in Hurstbourne Acres off Hurstbourne Lane _ a project that
will be announced Monday.
   In Chicago, Sears corporate spokesman Bill Rule said that Sears
has scheduled a news conference for Monday at the Louisville Chamber
of Commerce on the catalog center.
   Last Wednesday the city council of Hurstbourne Acres approved
Silliman's plans for a one-story office building with 48,800 square
feet of space.
   And last Thursday, the city-county Planning Commission approved
plans by NTS for a two-story office building with about 75,000
square feet of space near Interstate 64.
