<2ND_LINE>PM-Brazil,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dock Strike Paralyzes Brazilian Ports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of striking dock
workers demanding higher pay have closed the nation's main ports,
officials said today.
   Portobras, the government agency that operates the ports, said
about 30,000 workers walked off their jobs Tuesday in 12 of Brazil's
30 ports, including Santos, Latin America's biggest port. The strike
continued today, but there were few details of how widespread it was.
   About $3 million has been lost in uncollected port fees, the
Portobras press office said.
   In Santos, 45 miles from Sao Paulo, the strike was causing daily
losses of about $1.1 million, officials said.
   About 52,000 tons of products a day, ranging from automobiles and
iron ore to soybeans and chemical products, ``are being left
unhandled aboard 25 ships that are docked in Santos,'' said Sergio
Coelho, a spokesman for the Sao Paulo State Dock Co.
   Carlos Eduardo da Silva, one of the directors of the Santos Dock
Workers Union, said in a telephone interview that workers were
demanding a 38 percent wage increase. Neither he nor Coelho would
say what the average salary of a dock worker was.
   Coelho said the dock company has not made any wage offers to the
strikers ``because we barely have enough money to pay December's
salaries.''
   Inflation in Brazil is running at more than 1,000 percent a year.
   On Nov. 23, workers at the nation's largest steel mill ended a
17-day strike marked by a clash with soldiers that left three
strikers dead and scores injured. The workers, at the state-owned
National Steel Co. in Volta Redonda northwest of Rio, voted to
accept a proposed wage increase.
</TEXT>
