<DOCNO> AP881214-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-88 1129EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-US-EEC     12-14 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-US-EEC,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yeutter Predicts U.S. Will Prevail On Agriculture Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States will prevail in its fight
with Europe over agricultural subsidies because its position is ``on
the side of the angels,'' U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter
said Wednesday.
   Yeutter, who is being considered for the post of Agriculture
Secretary in the Bush administration, also said the United States
will retaliate against the European Economic Community if it
implements a Jan. 1 ban on importing hormone-treated meat.
   The United States has already decided it will strike against some
European imports, Yeutter told the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, ``and
that decision stands.''
   He said the United States has not found any evidence that
hormone-treated animals endanger consumers' health, ``and therefore
this is an illegal trade barrier.'' The ball is now in Europe's
court ``and time is getting short,'' he said.
   The 12-nation EEC said last week it intends to implement the ban,
which had already been put off for one year at the request of the
United States. The measure would affect some $170 million worth of
U.S. meat.
   One possible compromise offered by the EEC would exempt meat
which is used for pet food and which accounts for about 50 percent
of the imports. EEC officials have said the Americans rejected that
solution because they are determined to hold out for all or nothing
as a matter of principle.
   Prospects for a compromise appeared to dim last week as relations
between the two trading giants soured over an unrelated dispute
about government support for farmers.
   The impasse blocked other progress at an international trade
meeting of 100 nations in Montreal and left residues of bitterness
on both sides of the Atlantic. To avert collapse of the Montreal
meeting, which was a mid-term review of the four-year Uruguay Round
of trade negotiations, participants agreed to meet again in the
first week of April in Geneva.
   ``Let's hope reason will prevail'' in Geneva, Yeutter said. If
the agriculture issue is not solved, he warned, ``there's obviously
jeopardy to the entire Uruguay Round.''
   The controversy stems from a U.S. demand that all members of the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) abolish their farm
supports which distort trade on the world market. The EEC, under
strong pressure from its large rural population, advocates reduction
in subsidies but not elimination.
   ``We're on the side of the angels on this issue,'' Yeutter said,
``and everyone, including our European allies, knows this.''
   The United States contends that elimination of farm supports will
lower government expenditure and ease the burden on consumers and
taxpayers around the world.
   Yeutter predicted political pressure on the Europeans would mount
between now and April, ``and political pressure can generate
political will'' to change positions. The pressure is expected to
come from agricultural exporters such as Argentina and Australia,
whose farmers are having trouble competing against the subsidized
European and American farm exports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881214-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-88 1138EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   12-14 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened narrowly mixed
today on the Chicago Board of Trade with little fresh news in the
markets to influence prices.
   The quiet opening in the corn and wheat pits suggested traders
were still holding to expectations for large-scale export sales of
U.S. grain to the Soviet Union, analysts said.
   Reports of a pickup in soybean meal exports last week lent some
support to the soybean complex but buying interest was limited by a
change to wetter weather in the South American soybean belt, where
planting continues.
   ``We saw some reasonably good shower activity in Brazil yesterday
and over the next few days it looks like scattered light showers,''
said Dale Gustafson, a grain-market analyst with Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc. in Chicago. ``That's keeping the market from getting
too strong here at the moment.''
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 1 cent higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.27 a bushel; corn was
unchanged to 1 cent lower with December at $2.65 a bushel; oats were
unchanged across the board with March at $2.20{ a bushel; soybeans
were unchanged to 2 cents higher with January at $7.65{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were slightly higher while pork futures were mixed
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .20 cent to .35 cent higher with Decem  The so-called
Montgomery Amendment was passed by Congress after
governors in some states began objecting _ and blocking _ deployment
of their National Guard units on training assignments to Central
America.
   Rep. G.V. ``Sonny'' Montgomery, D-Miss., who wrote the provision,
last week condemned the 8th Circuit ruling.
   ``If 50 governors are allowed to veto Guard missions because they
don't like the way our foreign policy is administered, it would have
an adverse impact on training and would raise questions about the
availability of the Guard to meet its considerable defense
responsibilities,'' he said.
   Pending the results of any appeal, the only states affected by
the ruling at those in the 8th Circuit: Arkansas, Iowa, Minnesota,
Missouri, Nebraska, North Dakota and South Dakota.
</TEXT>
