<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Tenneco-CorporateChanges     12-14 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tenneco-Corporate Changes,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tenneco Reorganizes Corporate Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tenneco Inc. announced today it is reorganizing
its corporate office following the sale of Tenneco Oil Co. and the
retirement and resignation of two top executives.
   John P. Diesel, Tenneco Inc. president, elected to take early
retirement at age 62 and Joe B. Foster, 54, executive vice
president, resigned to pursue other interests, a company statement
said. Both also will resign from the Tenneco Board of Directors.
   Their resignations are effective Dec. 31.
   The corporate office now will be comprised of James L. Ketelsen,
58, chairman of the board and chief executive officer; Kenneth W.
Reese, 58, executive vice president and member of the board and
Allen T. McInnes, 51, executive vice president.
   ``The corporate office will continue to provide direction,
financial guidance and management assistance to help Tenneco's
industrial businesses maintain and further their industry leadership
positions,'' Ketelsen said. ``We will continue our policy of
allowing divisional companies substantial autonomy in the conduct of
their day-to-day operations.''
   In October, Houston-based Tenneco announced it had sold Tenneco
Oil Co. _ which had made up 22 percent of the corporation's total
revenue _ for about $7.3 billion to several buyers.
   Tenneco is a diversified industrial corporation with major
business interests in natural gas pipelines, farm and construction
equipment, automotive parts, shipbuilding, packaging, chemicals and
minerals.
</TEXT>
