<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-88 1307EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Caesars     12-14 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Caesars,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trump Indicates He May Seek Control Of Caesars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Developer Donald Trump has notified
the federal government that he wants to buy 15 percent or more of
Caesars World Inc. stock and that he may seek controlling interest,
the hotel and casino company says.
   In a statement issued late Tuesday, Caesars officials said they
were notified that Trump has asked the government for a ruling on
whether his investment in Caesars would violate federal antitrust
laws.
   The disclosure sent Caesars' common stock sharply higher today.
In midday trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Caesars was up $4
a share to $29.25.
   But gaming analysts said Trump, who already owns two casinos in
Atlantic City and is building a third, would face regulatory
obstacles to a move on Caesars in both Nevada, where Caesars is
based, and New Jersey, which prohibits single ownership of no more
than three casinos.
   The Los Angeles-based Caesars owns the highly profitable Caesars
Hotel Casino here and the Caesars Palace and Caesars Tahoe casino
hotels in Nevada.
   Neither Trump's filing nor Caesars' statement indicated how much
Caesars stock Trump may already own. Tuesday's filing was made under
the Hart-Scott-Rodino Act, which requires companies or individuals
to seek such a ruling once they have acquired $15 million worth of
stock in a company.
   At Tuesday's closing price of $25.25 per share, that would
translate to about 590,000 shares, or about 2.4 percent of Caesar's
24.5 million common shares outstanding.
   Susan Heilbron, executive vice president of the Turmp
Organization, said Trump had no comment on the filing other than to
confirm that it was made. She declined to say how much Caesars'
stock, if any, Trump already owns.
   According to the Caesars' statement, Trump indicated he ``has the
good faith intention, subject to price, availability and necessary
approvals, if any,'' to acquire 15 percent of Caesar's stock.
   Trump's filing also said he ``may decide to seek control of
(Caesars) through the acquisition of 50 percent (or) more of the
outstanding voting securities.''
   ``Due to the confusing content of this notice, (Caesars) is
unable to ascertain Mr. Trump's plans at this time and has no
further comment,'' the company said in its release.
   One gaming analyst, Marvin Roffman of Janney Montgomery Scott
Inc. in Philadelphia, said he doubts that Trump is serious about
making a move to acquire Caesars, and said any such move would face
serious regulatory opposition in New Jersey and Nevada.
   ``The gaming board in Nevada has come out and said it does not
particularly relish hostile takeovers, and I can tell you that this
would be a hostile takeover because the company will vigorously
defend its independence,'' he said.
   New Jersey gaming regulators have also strongly opposed hostile
takeovers of casino companies.
   Trump now owns Trump Plaza and Trump Castle casino hotels in
Atlantic City and is building the massive Taj Mahal casino hotel,
which should be complete in 15 months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881214-0277 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-88 1325EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-FrostBros.Sale     12-14 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Frost Bros. Sale,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Australian Company to Buy Second Texas Specialty Retailer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In its second rescue of a troubled Texas retailer,
an Australian property and retail company has signed a letter of
intent to buy the Frost Bros. chain for an undisclosed sum.
   Hooker Corp. Ltd. bought 80 percent of the Houston-based Sakowitz
Inc. in November 1987, bringing it out of bankruptcy. Robert T.
Sakowitz, the chain's chairman and a member of its founding family,
held the remaining 20 percent.
   On Tuesday, Hooker announced that L.J. Hooker Group, its wholly
owned subsidiary, would fold the San Antonio-based Frost chain into
Sakowitz, operate all the stores under the Sakowitz name and put
Robert Sakowitz in charge of the combined operation.
   Both chains are high-priced merchandisers catering to wealthy
customers and emphasizing upscale women's apparel. Both also operate
four stores. All the Sakowitz outlets are in Houston, while Frost's
are in Houston, San Antonio and Austin.
   In a prepared statement, Hooker Executive Chairman George Herscu
said, ``The proposed expansion of Sakowitz Inc. is a rare
opportunity to bring together two of the finest names in Texas
specialty retailing targeted to the upscale and quality-conscious
customer.''
   Frost Bros. filed for protection from its creditors under Chapter
11 of federal bankruptcy laws in New York in April. The financially
troubled retailer had gone public in an effort to improve its
financial picture, but that plan fell through with the stock market
crash of Oct. 19, 1987.
   Sam Wyly and his wife, Torie Steele Wyly, of Dallas, had bought
the chain from Manhatten Industries of New York for an estimated $50
million in August 1986, and Wyly said at the time he would
concentrate on the ``Mercedes Benz niche'' in retailing.
   Between the purchase date and the bankruptcy filing, the number
of stores was cut from 13 to nine. More stores were closed after
filing, including two in Houston _ at the Galleria and Memorial City
shopping centers. Frost continues to operate its third Houston store
near the exclusive River Oaks neighborhood.
   The company had 1985 revenue of $120 million. More recent figures
were not available.
   Hooker, based in Sydney, Australia, is an aggressive buyer of
U.S. retailers and a real estate developer in the United States and
Australia.
   It bought 80 percent of Sakowitz in 1987 for $7.5 million under
an amended plan of reorganization filed in federal bankruptcy court.
   Sakowitz was the nation's last remaining high-fashion speciality
retailer controlled by a founding family member. It filed for
Chapter 11 reorganization protection in the wake of financial
troubles stemming partly from the economic slump in the Southwest.
   At the time of the filing in 1985, Sakowitz had 17 stores and six
boutiques in Texas, Oklahoma and Arkansas, a number of which since
have been sold.
   Other Hooker Corp. holdings include B. Altman and Co., the New
York-based department store chain which it acquired in October 1987
for an undisclosed price, and Parisian Inc., the Birmingham, Ala.,
specialty retailer which it acquired along with Parisian's major
shareholders in September 1987 in a $252 million buyout.
   Hooker also is developing four regional shopping malls in the
United States, averaging 1.5 million square feet each.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881214-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-88 1315EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Trade 5thLd-Writethru f0129 12-14 0852</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade, 5th Ld-Writethru, f0129,0877</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Gap Smallest in 3 Months</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf pvs, ``I think, to restore dropped word
``heavy.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. trade deficit narrowed to $10.35
billion in October, the smallest imbalance in three months, the
government reported today.
   The Commerce Department said that the merchandise trade gap
between what the United States imports and what it sells overseas
fell by 3.1 percent from a September deficit of $10.67 billion.
   The decline represented the second consecutive monthly
improvement. But many analysts were unimpressed, saying after
monthly fluctuations, the deficit has been essentially flat for
several months.
   ``I think the improvement in the trade deficit has stalled out,''
said Allen Sinai, chief economist of the Boston Co. ``We still have
a very heavy flow of imported goods, especially on the manufacturing
side.''
   The Reagan administration was more optimistic. Commerce Secretary
C. William Verity cited the progress made so far, noting that
exports have climbed by 28 percent over the past 10 months.
   ``While the trend continues to be favorable, our trade deficit is
still very large. Eliminating it, which is our goal, poses a major
challenge,'' Verity said in a statement.
   Financial markets, which in the past have reacted violently to
disappointing trade figures, for the most part shrugged off today's
report. The Dow Jones industrial average had fallen by about 5
points shortly before midday.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve Board said that the
operating rate at U.S. factories, mines and utilities rose 0.2
percentage point last month to 84.2 percent, its highest level in
nine years.
   That report, which was in line with economists' predictions, is
likely to intensify cononcern about inflation. As capacity use edges
toward 85 percent, economists fear factories will have trouble
producing enough goods to meet demand, leading to shortages and
price increases.
   The October trade improvement came from a 1.7 percent drop in
imports, which declined to $38.02 billion, on a seasonally adjusted
basis.
   This decline offset a smaller 1.1 percent drop in U.S. exports,
which edged down to $27.67 billion.
   Even with the small setback in exports, U.S. overseas sales
remained near record high levels. For the first 10 months of this
year, export sales are running 28.3 percent above the same period in
1987.
   This remarkable surge in export sales has been responsible for
almost half of America's overall economic growth this year as
American manufacturers have hired workers and stepped up output to
meet demand.
   Through October, the overall merchendise trade deficit has been
running at an annual rate of $136.1 billion, 20 percent below the
all-time high imbalance of $170.3 billion recorded last year.
   President-elect Bush cited this improvement during the
presidential campaign as proof that the Reagan administration's
policies of solving the country's trade woes were working.
   The administration launched an effort in September 1985 to drive
the value of the dollar lower to make American goods more
competitive on overseas markets while driving up the price of
imports.
   The effort took far longer to bear fruit than many had expected
and has to this day failed to halt the steady increase in imports,
which are running 8.3 percent higher so far this year over 1987.
   The $10.35 billion October deficit was the lowest since a $9.47
billion July imbalance. That had been the smallest deficit since
December 1984.
   The trade report, U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter said,
was ``good news on which to close out 1988. He added that the
deficit was now falling ``at a satisfactory pace.''
   Today's good news on trade followed a report Tuesday showing that
the deficit in the broadest measure of trade, the current account,
fell to $30.89 billion in the July-September quarter, the lowest
level in three years.
   The current account method adds the value of investments and
services to the value of goods reflected in today's report.
   Many economists are worried that despite the dramatic declines in
the trade deficit this year, the improvement is in danger of
stalling next year, a development that could push the country into a
recession.
   Some economists contend that the dollar must fall further to make
U.S. goods even more competitive and dampen Americans' appetite for
imports. Other analysts are urging the Bush administrative to waste
no time in launching an aggressive effort to open more foreign
markets to American products.
   The October report is likely to provide ammunition to these
critics because of a 34.1 percent jump in the trade deficit with
Japan. The trade imbalance with Japan, the largest with any country,
surged to $5.5 billion in October, the highest it has been in a year.
   The deficit with Taiwan was unchanged at $1.4 billion while the
deficit with Western Europe rose to $1.1 billion, $200 million
higher than in October.
   The deficits with individual countries are not adjusted to take
into account normal monthly variations in trade flows. Before the
seasonal adjustment, the overall deficit would have been $11.75
billion, reflecting the fact that October is a big import month as
retailers stock up for the Christmas season.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
