<HEAD>Shares Close Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed higher Wednesday after a late
flurry of activity in the oil sector provided a boost in an
otherwise dull trading session.
   A few minutes before the market closed, British Petroleum Co.
confirmed it was negotiating the sale of part of its minerals
business to RTZ Corp. Then the market was swept by an unconfirmed
rumor that London and Scottish Marine Oil PLC had completed the
long-awaited sale of its 25.2 percent stake in Enterprise Oil PLC.
   Share prices of the companies involved moved sharply higher,
providing a brief flurry of activity at the end of a quiet session.
   The index spent most of the day in negative territory, as the
market concentrated on its previous concerns about recent increases
in U.K. interest rates.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index rose 3.5
points, or 0.2 percent, to close at 1,756.1. At its low, the index
was down 10.9 points from Tuesday's close.
   Volume was a modest 447.1 million shares, up from 473.9 million
shares on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
