<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell Wednesday against all major
currencies in Europe after the U.S. government reported that the
nation's October trade deficit was only slightly narrower than
market forecasts.
   Gold prices fell in Zurich but were unchanged in London.
   Although the trade deficit narrowed to $10.35 billion in October
from $10.67 billion in September, the Commerce Department
announcement sparked a slight dollar sell-off, dealers said.
   ``The figures were actually quite good, but no one wants to buy
dollars,'' said a dealer at a large bank in Frankfurt, West Germany.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.8335 from $1.8280 late
Tuesday.
   In Tokyo, where trading finished before the report was released,
the dollar rose 0.29 Japanese yen to a closing 123.35 yen. But later
in London, the dollar dropped to 122.60 yen.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday's
rate, included: 1.7365 West German marks, down from 1.7410; 1.4630
Swiss francs, down from 1.4705; 5.9350 French francs, down from
5.9775; 1.9590 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9715; 1,279.50 Italian
lire, down from 1,286.50; and 1.1986 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1995.
   Gold prices moved in a narrow range in light European trading.
   In Zurich, gold fell to a late bid of $420 a troy ounce from
$420.45 late Tuesday. In London, gold was quoted at a late bid of
$420.75 an ounce, unchanged from Tuesday's late bid.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold fell 16 cents to close at a bid of
$421.38 an ounce.
   Silver bullion dropped in London to a late bid of $6.16 a troy
ounce from $6.17 late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
