<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybeans Surge On Strength In Meal Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures closed sharply higher Wednesday on
the Chicago Board of Trade, in line with a strong late rally in
soybean meal linked to speculation about increased export sales,
analysts said.
   Corn prices also closed higher while wheat futures finished
narrowly mixed.
   Soybean meal traders noted recent purchases of U.S. meal by
Venezuela, ``and there were rumors of Soviet interest as well, and
that seemed to be the driving force,'' said Dale Gustafson, a
grain-market analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
   ``The strength in meal allowed the beans to rally and was
successful in bringing up (soybean) oil as well,'' he said.
   Meal for delivery in January closed $5.10 higher at $250.20 per
metric ton; soybeans gained as much as 14} cents a bushel.
   Corn also was supported by rumors of Soviet buying interest but
wheat trading was light amid a lack of fresh news affecting that
market.
   At the close, wheat was 1 cent lower to { cent higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.26{ a bushel; corn was 1{
cents to 4{ cents higher with December at $2.66} a bushel; oats were
} cent to 2 cents higher with December at $2.11{ a bushel; soybeans
