<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-88 1544EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-BP     12-14 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-BP,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BP in Talks To Sell Minerals Operations to RTZ</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Petroleum Co. PLC said Wednesday it is
negotiating to sell its minerals operations to RTZ Corp. PLC, a deal
that analysts said could generate $3 billion to $4 billion for BP.
   BP said the talks were exclusively with RTZ, a British mining
company with interests worldwide, and exclude any minerals
businesses of BP Canada.
   Rumors of the talks have circulated for the last week and have
helped drive British Petroleum's shares up and RTZ's down.
   British Petroleum did not elaborate on the statement except to
say that a further announcement will be made in due course.
   Its minerals interests include activities in gold, silver, copper
and uranium mines in the United States, Australia, Papua New Guinea,
Mexico and South Africa.
   British Petroleum has considered selling off its gold operations
for some time. In September, it postponed indefinitely the pricing
date for an initial public offering of about 15 percent of the gold
subsidiary.
   As speculation about the talks mounted last week, some analysts
said British Petroleum would use the proceeds of the sale to buy
into existing businesses, possibly even including a bid for Unocal
Corp. of the United States.
   Other analysts noted that it could use the cash earned either to
reduce debt or buy back shares held by the Kuwait Investment Office.
The Kuwaiti government body currently owns 21.68 percent of British
Petroleum and has been told by the British government to reduce its
holding to 9.9 percent, within a provisional timetable of a year.
   The money could give British Petroleum flexibility in bargaining
with Kuwait over a sale price for some of the 700 million shares,
which at current market prices have a total value of about 1.8
billion pounds _ equaling about $3.3 billion at current exchange
rates.
   British Petroleum shares closed Wednesday at the equivalent of
$4.74 a share, up 11 cents. RTZ's shares fell 11 cents to finish at
$7.01 a share.
   Analysts said it could take weeks to complete negotiations over
the sale of the minerals businesses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
