<1ST_LINE>d f BC-Italy-ChemicalGroup     12-14 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Italy-Chemical Group,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Montedison Board Approves Big Joint Venture With Enichem</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The board of Montedison on Wednesday approved
a joint venture with Italy's state-owned Enichem to create a
chemical company that is among the 10 largest in the world, with
annual sales equaling about $10 billion.
   The approval was the final hurdle for creating the new company,
Enimont, which is scheduled to begin operations Jan. 1.
   Montedison Chairman Raul Gardini told a news conference that
Enimont will have an initial six-month transitory regime that could
be phased out earlier if Parliament approves a legislation designed
to give Montedison a major tax break.
   Enichem, the chemical unit of Italy's energy group Ente Nazionale
Idrocarburi (ENI), and Montedison each will own 40 percent of
Enimont. The balance will be held privately.
   The merger of Montedison's bulk chemical interests with Enichem
into Enimont will play a key role in cutting Montedison's level of
consolidated debt. The private group, which is 42 percent owned by
Feruzzi Finanziaria of the Ferruzzi family, will transfer around
$2.9 billion of its debt to Enimont.
   At the same time, the proposed new tax legislation will cut to
$288 million the amount owed in taxes for the joint venture. Under
the present law Montedison would owe as much as $1.1 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
