<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-General Mills,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Mills Second-Quarter Earnings Flat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Mills Corp. on Wednesday reported its
second quarter net earnings were unchanged from a year earlier,
although sales edged higher during the period.
   The food and restaurant company posted a profit of $79.6 million,
or 97 cents a share. Earnings per share totaled 90 cents per share
in the year-earlier quarter because the average number of
outstanding shares was higher, the company said.
   Sales during the three months ended Nov. 27 rose to $1.4 billion
from $1.3 billion in the same period last year.
   For the first six months of fiscal 1988, including results from
discontinued operations, General Mills posted net earnings of $369.5
million, or $4.50 a share, compared with $156.8 million, or $1.77 a
share, in the first 26 weeks of fiscal 1987.
   Results from continuing operations for the first six months of
the year were $170.4 million, or $2.07 a share, compared with $155.1
million, or $1.75 a share, for the same period a year ago.
   Sales for the first six months increased to $2.79 billion from
$2.54 billion.
   Sales and operating profits from consumer foods grew 4 percent in
the second quarter, with breakfast cereals gaining market share in a
total market that grew 5 percent in volume, Chairman Bruce Atwater
said.
   Established Red Lobster restaurants posted an 8 percent increase
in unit sales in the second quarter. The company added 12 new Red
Lobsters converted from the 27-unit chain of Seafood Broiler
restaurants that it acquired in California.
</TEXT>
