<1ST_LINE>u f AM-OilReport     12-14 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Report,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Petroleum Imports Continued To Rise In November</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Petroleum imports rose sharply in November and
domestic crude oil production took its biggest monthly dip this
year, the American Petroleum Institute reported Wednesday.
   Imports jumped 14.1 percent to an average 7.95 million barrels a
day from 6.97 million barrels in November 1987, with imports of
gasoline and other refined products reaching their highest level
since 1974, according to API's Monthly Statistical Report.
   Daily domestic crude oil production fell 4.3 percent _ the
biggest decline this year _ to an average of 8.04 million barrels a
day, due mainly to a slowdown in output in the lower 48 states.
Alaska production remained steady at around 2 million barrels a day,
the report said.
   Analysts said strong demand in November continued to consume the
growing imports as total supplies of crude oil and refined products
declined 3.6 percent compared with the same time last year.
   The institute said lower world crude prices helped boost imports
for the first 11 months of 1988 to their highest level since 1980 as
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries continued its
runaway production.
   However, OPEC members agreed last month to lower cartel
production in the first six months of 1989. World crude prices have
firmed slightly since the accord in anticipation of a cutback.
   In November, crude oil imports averaged 5.3 million barrels a
day, up 7.8 percent from November 1987, the report said.
   Product imports rose 29 percent to an average 2.7 million barrels
a day. Daily gasoline imports reached a new high of 630,000 barrels
for the month, up 80,000 barrels a day from a year ago. Distillate
and residual fuel oil imports also were strong.
   In the past three years, daily imports are up by 2.2 million
barrels, with increasing demand accounting for about two-thirds of
the increase and declining domestic production accounting for most
of the remainder, the API said.
   But despite high imports, total inventories fell by 5 million
barrels in November. API said inventories have fallen about 18
million barrels since July, or more than 50 million barrels after
accounting for seasonal factors.
   Combined deliveries surged more than 1.3 million barrels a day,
an 8.1 percent increase from the year-ago period.
   Gasoline deliveries rose 3.6 percent, or nearly 5 million
barrels, even as motorists began cutting back on travel. Gasoline
production rose 1.5 percent while gasoline stocks declined 6 million
barrels from last November.
   Distillate deliveries rose 7.3 percent despite continued mild
weather. Analysts said the rise probably reflected investors taking
advantage of weak prices.
   The report also said utilization of the nation's refineries
increased to 83.2 percent from 82.3 percent last November.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881214-0292 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-88 1733EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     12-14 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0543</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar retreated Wednesday, hurt by what
money dealers called rumors of a hike in West German interest rates
and a negative market reaction to the monthly U.S. trade report.
   Gold prices rose slightly in U.S. trading after easing marginally
abroad. Republic National Bank quoted bullion at $421 a troy ounce
as of 4 p.m. EST, up from $419.50 at the same time Tuesday.
   Foreign-exchange strategists said speculation that the West
German central bank would tighten domestic credit conditions on
Thursday raised demand for the West German mark and consequently
increased the supply of dollars in the market, pushing down the U.S.
currency's value.
   Pressure on the dollar intensified after the Commerce Department
said the U.S. merchandise trade deficit narrowed to $10.35 billion
in October from $10.67 billion the month before. Although the
shortfall was the smallest in three months, the market had
anticipated an imbalance of about $10.5 billion.
   ``The figures came out in line with expectations, and since
there's overriding bearish sentiment to the dollar, people just
resumed selling it,'' said Stuart Yannalfo, a trader at the New York
commodities futures firm Refco Inc. ``The only thing that could have
prevented it would have been a really good number, like $7 or $8
billion.''
   The monthly trade figures vary widely but have enormous potential
to affect the dollar's value because they are considered one of the
most visible indicators of U.S. competitiveness and economic
strength.
   A widening deficit suggests exports are weakening and the dollar
will fall, while a narrowing shortfall suggests exports are
strengthening and the dollar will rise.
   In Tokyo, where markets closed before the trade report was
released, the dollar rose 0.29 Japanese yen to 123.35 yen. Later in
London, the dollar dropped to 122.60 yen. By the time trading ended
in New York the dollar fetched 122.67 yen, down from 123.29 yen late
Tuesday.
   The British pound rose in London to $1.8335 from $1.8280 late
Tuesday. In New York sterling fetched $1.8295, up from $1.8190 late
Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with rates late
Tuesday, included: 1.7374 West German marks, down from 1.7497;
1.4655 Swiss francs, down from 1.4717; 1.2020 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.1999; 5.9390 French francs, down from 5.9790; and 1,285.25
Italian lire, down from 1,288.71.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with rates late
Tuesday, included: 1.7365 marks, down from 1.7410; 1.4630 Swiss
francs, down from 1.4705; 5.9350 French francs, down from 5.9775;
1.9590 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9715; 1,279.50 Italian lire, down
from 1,286.50; and 1.1986 Canadian dollas, down from 1.1995.
   Gold prices moved in a narrow range. At the Commodity Exchange in
New York, gold for current delivery rose $1.70 a troy ounce to
$421.50. In London, gold fetched $420.75 an ounce, unchanged from
late Tuesday; in Zurich gold fell 45 cents to $420, and in Hong Kong
it fell 16 cents to $421.38.
   Silver bullion for current delivery rose 0.9 cent a troy ounce to
$6.177 on New York's Comex. In London, silver fell 1 cent to $6.16
an ounce.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881214-0293 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-88 1742EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Ford Bjt   12-14 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ford, Bjt,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Looking for Another Good Year in Autos</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for AMs bjt item slugged Ford-Gasoline Tax.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. still is shopping for
financial industry acquisitions and hopes to land one before tax
breaks expire at year's end, Vice Chairman Harold Poling said
Wednesday.
   Poling said any acquisition, likely to be one or more savings and
loan institutions, could make Ford's wholly-owned subsidiary First
Nationwide Bank the nation's biggest savings bank. First Nationwide
now is the sixth-largest.
   First Nationwide in September failed in its bid to acquire
American Savings and Loan Association, of Stockton, Calif., the
nation's biggest insolvent thrift.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board instead provided $2 billion in
federal assistance to Robert M. Bass Group of Fort Worth, Texas to
acquire American in the largest government thrift rescue yet.
   ``We intend to continue to pursue diversification in the
financial services area,'' Poling said during an end-of-the-year
review with reporters. ``Our specific goal is to do a good job.
Becoming the largest isn't the objective. It's growth.''
   Poling also said it appears that 1988 will be the auto industry's
second-best sales year ever, with car and light truck sales at 15.6
million to 15.7 million. The industry record of 16.3 million in
sales was set in 1986.
   He said the 15.4 million estimate for the 1989 calendar year
would be ``down from this year, but still a good industry.''
   ``I'd be worried when our (market) share begins to run into
problems,'' he said. Ford's U.S. market share for cars is 21.7
percent, he said.
   During the meeting, Poling also said:
   _Buyer incentives would continue during the coming year, but ``I
don't see us leading the charge.'' He said Ford would remain
competitive when other automakers offer incentives.
   _Discussions are under way for assembly of a car, probably
modeled on Ford's West German-made Scorpio, in the Soviet Union. The
car probably would be made in an existing or new plant in the Gorky
area.
   Poling also said Ford's North American earnings likely will be
down from last year, resulting in smaller profit-sharing payments to
Ford employees early in 1989.
   Earlier this week, General Motors Corp. announced profit-sharing
payments of about $200 for each hourly and salaried worker, the
first time since 1985 that the nation's No. 1 automaker has made
such payments.
   ``I think it (Ford's profit-sharing payment) will be more than
$200,'' Poling said, smiling.
   Poling said a proposal for a 15-cent-per-gallon gasoline tax
increase should be considered by the incoming Bush administration
only if other deficit reduction measures, especially federal
spending cuts, prove unsuccessful.
   He said a 5-cent-a-year phase-in of such a tax increase would
soften the blow on the auto industry, and provisions such as tax
credits could be made for low-income taxpayers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881214-0294 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-88 1745EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AutoSales Bjt   12-14 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sales Slump In Early December</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of U.S.-made cars and light trucks fell 11
percent in early December compared with a burst of incentive-driven
sales in the same period a year ago, figures released Wednesday
showed.
   The companies said they sold an average of 29,610 vehicles during
each of the nine selling days in the Dec. 1-10 period this year,
compared with an average of 33,251 during the same period last year,
when there also were nine selling days.
   Car sales fell 10.5 percent and light truck sales dropped 11.7
percent in early December.
   Analysts said the declines weren't worrisome because of the
revival of incentives during the period last year.
   ``They started putting on some heavy-duty incentives'' in early
December last year, said analyst Kathleen Heaney of Nikko Securities
Co. International Inc. ``You've got a tough time to compare it
with.''
   Mary Ann Sudol of Fitch Investors agreed. ``That's hard to
read,'' she said. ``It's not surprising that they're down a little
bit, given that December is bad for auto sales anyway.
   ``In any (recent) 10-day period, you've had so much noise in the
period that it's hard to make a comparison,'' Sudol added. ``That
noise is incentives.''
   Both agreed that despite the early December slip, the industry is
healthy. As the calendar year draws to a close, the companies are
looking forward to what could be the second-best sales year in
history, behind the 16.3 million vehicles sold in 1986.
   For the year, sales by companies making cars and light trucks in
the United States have risen 6.9 percent in 1988 over 1987, going to
a daily rate of 37,949 this year compared with a daily rate of
35,499 last year.
   Among the Big Three, GM showed the largest early-December decline
in car sales, falling 12.9 percent to a daily rate of 8,906 cars in
1988 from 10,226 last year. GM's car sales were up 0.9 percent in
1988 over 1987 to a daily rate of 11,776 this year from 11,668 last
year.
   Ford's sales in early December fell 11.6 percent to a daily rate
of 5,582 this year compared with 6,316 in the same period last year.
But for the year, Ford's car sales have climbed 7.7 percent to an
average daily rate of 7,121 in 1988 compared with 6,612 in 1987.
   Chrysler said it sold cars at a daily rate of 2,673 in early
December this year compared with 2,979 during the same period last
year, a 10.3 percent decline. So far this year, Chrysler has sold
10.3 percent more cars, with a daily sales rate of 3,451 in 1988
compared with 3,130 last year.
