<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     12-14 0739</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0764</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coffee Futures Hit 4{-Month Highs On Supply Fears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Coffee futures prices rocketed to 4{-month highs Wednesday on New
York's Coffee, Sugar & Cocoa Exchange as a dockworkers strike in
Brazil ignited speculation about shriveling supplies.
   On other markets, prices of copper, precious metals, energy and
most agricultural futures also rose while stock-index futures
retreated.
   Coffee's day-long rally was ``an explosion'' featuring extremely
heavy volume, said Bert Ruiz, a coffee broker with Balfour Maclaine
Corp. in New York.
   Coffee settled 2.30 cents to 4.64 cents higher with the spot
December contract at $1.35 a pound and the heavily traded March
contract at $1.3342 a pound, the highest settlement price for either
contract since July 25.
   Analysts said the Brazilian dockworkers' strike, which began
Tuesday and halted shipments from the key coffee port of Santos, was
not expected to last long.
   But the strike focused the market's attention on dwindling
warehouse stocks of coffee just as consumption approaches its annual
peak, and on the steadily deteriorating crop-production outlook in
Brazil due to a drought in that country's major coffee-growing
regions.
   Ruiz said supplies that ordinarily arrive in the United States
from Central America at this time of year have been delayed by heavy
rains. And another 1 million bags of coffee recently authorized for
release onto the market by the International Coffee Organization's
price-support formula has not yet occurred, he said.
   Since June, Brazil's coffee-growing regions have received normal
monthly precipitation in only one month _ October, said Kim
Badenhop, an analyst wiht Merrill Lynch Capital Markets Inc. For the
year to date, precipitation in most of those areas is less than 50
percent of normal, he said.
   The dry weather has lessened the quality of the 1988-89 Brazilian
crop now being harvested and reduced projections for the 1989-90
crop from original estimates of more than 40 million bags to about
25 million bags.
   Copper futures rallied strongly on New York's Commodity Exchange
in technically inspired buying following two days of steep declines,
said Peter Cardillo, commodities trading adviser with Josephthal &
Co. in New York.
   Copper settled 2.20 cents to 4.20 cents higher with March at
$1.332 a pound.
   Platinum soared in a technical rebound from its recent lows while
gold and silver finished modestly higher, mainly in reaction to
platinum's gains and to strength in the energy market, Cardillo said.
   Platinum settled $9.50 to $14.50 higher on the New York
Mercantile Exchange with January at $604.50 a troy ounce. On the
Commodity Exchange, gold was $1.60 to $1.80 higher with February at
$425.70 a troy ounce; silver was 0.9 cent to 1.4 cents higher with
March at $6.305 a troy ounce.
   Energy futures prices surged on the New York Mercantile Exchange
following Norway's announcement that it would not increase
production of crude oil, informally supporting OPEC's new production
quotas designed to lift oil prices, analysts said.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 34 cents to 39 cents
higher with January at $16.37 a barrel; heating oil was 1.11 cents
to 1.86 cents higher with January at 51.13 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .34 cent to .88 cent higher with January at 43.72 cents
a gallon.
   Soybean futures settled sharply higher on the Chicago Board of
Trade in sympathy with a strong late rally in soybean meal linked to
talk of increased export sales, analysts said.
   Corn prices also closed higher while wheat futures finished
narrowly mixed.
   Wheat settled { cent lower to { cent higher with December at
$4.26} a bushel; corn was 1{ cents to 4{ cents higher with December
at $2.66} a bushel; oats were } cent to 2 cents higher with December
at $2.11{ a bushel; soybeans were 7{ cents to 14} cents higher with
January at $7.78\ a bushel.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, live cattle settled .15 cent
to .65 cent higher with December at 72.60 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were .30 cent to .57 cent higher with January at 84.30 cents
a pound; live hog futures were .03 cent to .68 cent higher with
December at 43.20 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .20 cent
lower to .42 cent higher with February at 44.92 cents a pound.
   Stock-index futures retreated moderately on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, where the contract for March delivery of the
Standard & Poor's 500 index settled 1.20 points lower at 278.40.
Each point is worth $500.
</TEXT>
