<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SteelImports     12-14 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Steel Imports,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tonnage Up, Market Share Holds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel imports rose 7.1 percent to 17.6 million
tons for the first 10 months of 1988, but strong domestic demand
held foreigners' share of the market near the goal of the U.S. quota
program, according to figures released Wednesday.
   Over 10 months of 1988, imports accounted for 20.4 percent of the
market, practically the goal set by the Reagan administration when
it introduced import quotas in 1984.
   Imports in October declined to 1.5 million tons from 1.64 million
tons in September and 1.61 million tons in October 1987.
   The figures, based on Commerce Department data, were released in
Washington, D.C., by the American Iron and Steel Institute.
   The rival American Institute for Imported Steel said that after
deducting 2.5 million tons of steel imports bought by domestic mills
for further processing, 10-month imports totaled 15 million tons, or
17.5 percent of the market. The percentage figure is well below the
18.5 percent target set for finished steel products.
   ``With (quotas) expiring in nine months and much being heard for
and against renewal, overriding factors in any decision in addition
to interest of domestic steel producers must also be those of
domestic steel users, fabricators and manufacturers of
steel-intensive products whose very existence creates the market for
both domestic steel producers and importers,'' said Erwin L. Klein,
president of the importers institute and vice chairman of the
importing firm Steelinter USA.
</TEXT>
