<HEAD>Pennwalt Tells Stockholders To Wait On Centaur Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennwalt Corp. told its shareholders
Wednesday to ignore an investor group's $100 a share buyout offer
until the chemical company's board of directors responds to it.
   Pennwalt spokeswoman Sue S. Kinard would not say when the board
plans to meet.
   The offer by Centaur Partners, whose principals are New York
financiers Abbey J. Butler and Melvyn J. Estrin, is worth about $765
million. Centaur already owns 12.7 percent of the company's
outstanding shares.
   On the New York Stock Exchange Wednesday,
   Pennwalt stock closed down 37{ cents at $98.25 a share Wednesday
on the New York Stock Exchange,
   Centaur Partners,owned 12.7 percent of the company's shares as of
Monday, when Centaur anounced the $100 per share offer.
   Some analysts have said the company, if sold piece by piece,
could be worth as much as $120 per share, or $900 million.
   Pennwalt has 9,000 employees and annual sales of more than $1
billion.
   Butler and Estrin, who have been courting the company for months,
have told Pennwalt Chairman Edwin E. Tuttle they have all the
financing needed to complete the deal.
   In its official tender offer submitted to the Securities and
Exchange Commission on Tuesday, Centaur Partners said it might sell
the company's agrichemical operations if their takeover succeeds.
   The partnership also said it would try to reduce overhead
expenses, which could mean layoffs. Centaur also said it would
follow through on Pennwalt's plan to sell the rest of its equipment
group.
   The partnership said it would review the company before
considering changes in Pennwalt's board of directors and corporate
structure.
   Six months ago, Centaur announced it had bought a large stake in
Pennwalt and in October said it had acquired 1 million shares, or
8.6 percent of the company.
   Pennwalt has responded to the offer by selling its drug and
equipment business and buying back about 40 percent of the
outstanding shares.
   On Tuesday, Moody's Investors Services Inc. said it was placing
Pennwalt's credit rating under review, saying it might downgrade it.
   ``The review is focusing on the changes in debt protection
afforded Pennwalt's bondholders and noteholders if the company is
acquired by Centaur or another entity,'' Moody's said.
