<1ST_LINE>r f BC-TexasAir-Dividends     12-14 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Texas Air-Dividends,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Air Withholding Preferred Stock Dividends</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Air Corp., parent of Continental and Eastern
airlines, said Wednesday it was withholding payment of preferred
stock dividends because its subsidiaries were not meeting earnings
objectives.
   The dividends, which Texas Air said would amount to about $5.2
million, affect 6.5 percent depository preferred stock, 12 percent
depository preferred stock, 6} percent cumulative convertible junior
preferred stock and 15 percent $20 cumulative preferred stock.
   Depending on the stock, dividends would have been payable between
Dec. 31, 1988 and Jan. 31, 1989.
   In a statement, Texas Air said its cash levels have been
substantial throughout the year and now exceed $700 million, but
provisions of the company's unsecured debt indentures incorporate
overall earnings objectives that have not been met.
   Texas Air singled out Eastern Airlines, which it said ``continues
to experience serious operating losses.
   Texas Air said the dividends would be paid later when profits
offset the cumulative effects of recent losses. The proposed sale of
assets such as the Eastern Shuttle also could aid in the resumption
of the dividend, the company said.
   Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo is proposing that the shuttle,
one of the airline's few profitable divisions, be sold to New York
real estate developer Donald Trump for $365 million. The deal is
being fought by Eastern's unions, which have been at odds with
Lorenzo.
   Eastern has lost $1 billion in the last decade, including a $113
million loss in the third quarter.
   Texas Air lost $494 million in the first nine months of 1988,
more than double the $200 million in losses amassed during the same
period a year ago.
</TEXT>
